# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chrysler-powertech-engine
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Chemically, aluminium is a post-transition metal in the boron group; as is common for the group, aluminium forms compounds primarily in the +3 oxidation state.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The aluminium cation Al3+ is small and highly charged; as such, it has more polarizing power, and bonds formed by aluminium have a more covalent character.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The strong affinity of aluminium for oxygen leads to the common occurrence of its oxides in nature.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is found on Earth primarily in rocks in the crust, where it is the third-most abundant element after oxygen and silicon, rather than in the mantle, and virtually never as the free metal.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] It is obtained industrially by mining bauxite, a sedimentary rock rich in aluminium minerals.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The discovery of aluminium was announced in 1825 by Danish physicist Hans Christian Ørsted.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The first industrial production of aluminium was initiated by French chemist Henri Étienne Sainte-Claire Deville in 1856.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium became much more available to the public with the Hall–Héroult process developed independently by French engineer Paul Héroult and American engineer Charles Martin Hall in 1886, and the mass production of aluminium led to its extensive use in industry and everyday life.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] In 1954, aluminium became the most produced non-ferrous metal, surpassing copper.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] In the 21st century, most aluminium was consumed in transportation, engineering, construction, and packaging in the United States, Western Europe, and Japan.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The standard atomic weight of aluminium is low in comparison with many other metals, giving it the low density responsible for many of its uses.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Despite its prevalence in the environment, no living thing is known to metabolize aluminium salts, but aluminium is well tolerated by plants and animals.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Because of the abundance of these salts, the potential for a biological role for them is of interest, and studies are ongoing.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium metal has an appearance ranging from silvery white to dull gray depending on its surface roughness.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium mirrors provides high reflectivity for light in the ultraviolet, visible (on par with silver), and far infrared regions.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is also good at reflecting solar radiation, although prolonged exposure to sunlight in air can deteriorate the reflectivity of the metal; this may be prevented if aluminium is anodized, which adds a protective layer of oxide on the surface.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The density of aluminium is 2.70 g/cm3, about one-third that of steel, much lower than other commonly encountered metals, making aluminium parts easily identifiable through their lightness.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium's low density compared to most other metals arises from the fact that its unit cell size is relatively large in proportion to the number of nucleons.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The only lighter metals are the metals of groups 1 and 2, which, apart from beryllium and magnesium, are too reactive for structural use (and beryllium is very toxic).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is not as strong or stiff as steel, but the low density makes up for this in the aerospace industry and for many other applications where light weight and relatively high strength are crucial.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Pure aluminium is quite soft and lacking in strength.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] In most applications, various aluminium alloys are used instead because of their higher strength and hardness.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The yield strength of pure aluminium is 7–11 MPa, while aluminium alloys have yield strengths ranging from 200 MPa to 600 MPa.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is ductile, with a percent elongation of 50–70%, and malleable allowing it to be easily drawn and extruded; it is also easily machined and cast.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is an excellent thermal and electrical conductor, and the amount of aluminium required to match the same amperage in copper weighs only half as much.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is capable of superconductivity, with a superconducting critical temperature of 1.2 kelvin and a critical magnetic field of about 100 gauss (10 milliteslas).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] It is paramagnetic and thus essentially unaffected by static magnetic fields.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] However, the high electrical conductivity means that it is strongly affected by alternating magnetic fields through the induction of eddy currents.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] An aluminium atom has 13 electrons with an electron configuration of [Ne] 3s2 3p1, with three electrons beyond a stable noble gas configuration.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Accordingly, the combined first three ionization energies of aluminium are far lower than the fourth ionization energy alone.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Such an electron configuration is shared with the other well-characterized members of its group, boron, gallium, indium, and thallium; it is also expected for nihonium.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium can surrender its three outermost electrons in many chemical reactions (see below).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The electronegativity of aluminium is 1.61 on the Pauling scale.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] A free aluminium atom has an atomic radius of 143 pm.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] With the three outermost electrons removed, the radius shrinks to 39 pm for a 4-coordinated atom or 53.5 pm for a 6-coordinated atom.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] At standard temperature and pressure, aluminium atoms (when not affected by atoms of other elements) form a face-centered cubic crystal system bound by metallic bonding provided by atoms' outermost electrons; hence, aluminium (at these conditions) is a metal.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] This crystal system is shared by many other metals, such as lead and copper; the size of a unit cell of aluminium is comparable to that of those other metals.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] This system, however, is not shared by the other members of its group: boron has ionization energies too high to allow metallization, thallium has a hexagonal close-packed structure, and gallium and indium have unusual structures that are not close-packed like those of aluminium and thallium.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The few electrons that are available for metallic bonding in aluminium are a probable cause for it being soft with a low melting point and low electrical resistivity.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium has one stable isotope, 27Al, which comprises virtually all of the naturally-occurring element.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] This is common for elements with an odd atomic number.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] It is therefore a mononuclidic element for standard atomic weight, which is determined completely by that isotope.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is useful in nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR), as its single stable isotope (though quadrupolar) has a high NMR sensitivity.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] All other isotopes of aluminium are radioactive.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The most stable of these is 26Al, with a half-life of 717,000 years.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] While it was present along with stable 27Al in the interstellar medium from which the Solar System formed (believed to have been produced by stellar nucleosynthesis also), no detectable amount could have survived the time since the formation of the planet.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] However, minute traces of 26Al are still produced from decay of argon in the atmosphere induced by ionizing radiation of cosmic rays.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The ratio of 26Al to 10Be has been used for the radiodating of geological processes over 105 to 106 year time scales, in particular transport, deposition, sediment storage, burial times, and erosion.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Most meteorite scientists believe that the energy released by the decay of 26Al was responsible for the melting and differentiation of some asteroids after their formation 4.55 billion years ago.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The other known isotopes of aluminium, with mass numbers ranging from 20 to 43, all have half-lives less than 7 minutes, as do the four detected metastable states.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium combines characteristics of pre- and post-transition metals.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Since it has few available electrons for metallic bonding, like the heavier group 13 elements, it has the characteristic physical properties of a post-transition metal, with longer-than-expected interatomic distances.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Furthermore, as Al3+ is a small and highly charged cation, it is strongly polarizing, and bonding in aluminium compounds tends towards covalency; this behavior is similar to that of beryllium (Be2+), displaying an example of a diagonal relationship.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The underlying core of electrons under aluminium's valence shell is that of the preceding noble gas, whereas those of the heavier group 13 elements gallium, indium, thallium, and nihonium also include a filled d-subshell and in some cases a filled f-subshell.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Hence, the inner electrons of aluminium shield the valence electrons almost completely, unlike those of the heavier group 13 elements.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] As such, aluminium is the most electropositive metal in its group, and its hydroxide is in fact more basic than that of gallium.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium also bears minor similarities to boron (a metalloid), which is in the same group: AlX3 compounds are valence isoelectronic to BX3 compounds (they have the same valence electronic structure), and both behave as Lewis acids and readily form adducts.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Additionally, one of the main motifs of boron chemistry is regular icosahedral structures, and aluminium forms an important part of many icosahedral quasicrystal alloys, including the Al–Zn–Mg class.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium has a high chemical affinity to oxygen, which renders it suitable for use as a reducing agent in the thermite reaction.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] A fine powder of aluminium reacts explosively on contact with liquid oxygen; under normal conditions, however, aluminium forms a thin oxide layer (~5 nm at room temperature) that protects the metal from further corrosion by oxygen, water, or dilute acid, a process termed passivation.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is not attacked by oxidizing acids because of its passivation.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] This allows aluminium to be used to store reagents such as nitric acid, concentrated sulfuric acid, and some organic acids.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] In hot, concentrated hydrochloric acid, aluminium reacts with water through evolution of hydrogen, and it reacts in aqueous sodium or potassium hydroxide at room temperature to form aluminates; protective passivation under these conditions is negligible.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is also corroded by dissolved chlorides, such as common sodium chloride.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The oxide layer on aluminium is also destroyed by contact with mercury due to amalgamation or by contact with salts of some electropositive metals.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] As such, the strongest aluminium alloys are less corrosion-resistant due to galvanic reactions with alloyed copper, and aluminium's corrosion resistance is greatly reduced by aqueous salts, particularly in the presence of dissimilar metals.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium reacts with most nonmetals upon heating, forming compounds such as aluminium nitride (AlN), aluminium sulfide (Al2S3), and the aluminium halides (AlX3).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] It also forms a wide range of intermetallic compounds involving metals from every group on the periodic table.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The vast majority of aluminium compounds, including all aluminium-containing minerals and all commercially significant aluminium compounds, feature aluminium in the oxidation state 3+.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The coordination number of such compounds varies, but generally Al3+ is either six- or four-coordinate.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Almost all compounds of aluminium(III) are colorless.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] In aqueous solution, Al3+ exists as the hexa-aqua cation [Al(H2O)6]3+, which has an approximate Ka of 10−5.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Such solutions are acidic because this cation can act as a proton donor and progressively hydrolyze until a precipitate of aluminium hydroxide, Al(OH)3, forms.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] This is useful for clarification of water, since the precipitate nucleates on suspended particles in the water, hence removing them.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Increasing the pH even further leads to the hydroxide dissolving again as aluminate, [Al(H2O)2(OH)4]−, is formed.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium hydroxide forms both salts and aluminates and dissolves in acid and alkali, as well as on fusion with acidic and basic oxides.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] This behavior of Al(OH)3 is termed amphoterism and is characteristic of weakly basic cations that form insoluble hydroxides and whose hydrated species can also donate their protons.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] One effect of this is that aluminium salts with weak acids are hydrolyzed in water to the aquated hydroxide and the corresponding nonmetal hydride: for example, aluminium sulfide yields hydrogen sulfide.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] However, some salts like aluminium carbonate exist in aqueous solution but are unstable as such.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Only incomplete hydrolysis takes place for salts with strong acids, such as the halides, nitrate, and sulfate.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] For similar reasons, anhydrous aluminium salts cannot be made by heating their "hydrates": hydrated aluminium chloride is in fact not AlCl3·6H2O but [Al(H2O)6]Cl3, and the Al–O bonds are so strong that heating is not sufficient to break them and form Al–Cl bonds.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Unlike the structures of the three heavier trihalides, aluminium fluoride (AlF3) features six-coordinate aluminium, which explains its involatility and insolubility as well as high heat of formation.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Each aluminium atom is surrounded by six fluorine atoms in a distorted octahedral arrangement, with each fluorine atom being shared between the corners of two octahedra.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Such {AlF6} units also exist in complex fluorides such as cryolite, Na3AlF6.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] AlF3 melts at 1,290 °C (2,354 °F) and is made by reaction of aluminium oxide with hydrogen fluoride gas at 700 °C (1,300 °F).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] With heavier halides, the coordination numbers are lower.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The other trihalides are dimeric or polymeric with tetrahedral four-coordinate aluminium centers.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium trichloride (AlCl3) has a layered polymeric structure below its melting point of 192.4 °C (378 °F) but transforms on melting to Al2Cl6 dimers.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] At higher temperatures those increasingly dissociate into trigonal planar AlCl3 monomers similar to the structure of BCl3.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium tribromide and aluminium triiodide form Al2X6 dimers in all three phases and hence do not show such significant changes of properties upon phase change.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] These materials are prepared by treating aluminium with the halogen.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The aluminium trihalides form many addition compounds or complexes.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Their Lewis acidic nature makes them useful as catalysts for the Friedel–Crafts reactions.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium trichloride has major industrial uses involving this reaction, such as in the manufacture of anthraquinones and styrene.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium trichloride is also often used as the precursor for many other aluminium compounds and as a reagent for converting nonmetal fluorides into the corresponding chlorides (a transhalogenation reaction).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium forms one stable oxide with the chemical formula Al2O3, commonly called alumina.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] It can be found in nature in the mineral corundum, the α-alumina phase.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Its crystalline form, corundum, is very hard (Mohs hardness 9), has a high melting point of 2,045 °C (3,713 °F), has very low volatility, is chemically inert, and is a good electrical insulator.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] It is often used in abrasives (such as sandpaper) as a refractory material and in ceramics.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] It is also the starting material for the electrolytic production of aluminium.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Sapphire and ruby are impure corundum contaminated with trace amounts of other metals.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The two main oxide-hydroxides, AlO(OH), are boehmite and diaspore.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] There are three main trihydroxides: bayerite, gibbsite, and nordstrandite, which differ in their crystalline structure (polymorphs).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Many other intermediate and related structures are also known.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Most of these Al-O-OH systems are produced from ores by a variety of wet processes using acid and bases.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Heating the hydroxides leads to the formation of corundum.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] These materials are of central importance to the production of aluminium and are themselves extremely useful.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Some mixed oxide phases are also very useful, such as spinel (MgAl2O4), Na-β-alumina (NaAl11O17), and tricalcium aluminate (Ca3Al2O6), an important mineral phase in Portland cement.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The only stable chalcogenides under normal conditions are aluminium sulfide (Al2S3), selenide (Al2Se3), and telluride (Al2Te3).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] All three are prepared by direct reaction of their elements at about 1,000 °C (1,800 °F) and quickly hydrolyze completely in water to yield aluminium hydroxide and the respective hydrogen chalcogenide.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] As aluminium is a small atom relative to these chalcogens, these have four-coordinate tetrahedral aluminium with various polymorphs having structures related to wurtzite, with two-thirds of the possible metal sites occupied either in an orderly (α) or random (β) fashion.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The sulfide also has a γ form related to γ-alumina and an unusual high-temperature hexagonal form where half the aluminium atoms have tetrahedral four-coordination and the other half have trigonal bipyramidal five-coordination.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Four pnictides – aluminium nitride (AlN), aluminium phosphide (AlP), aluminium arsenide (AlAs), and aluminium antimonide (AlSb) – are known.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] They are all III-V semiconductors isoelectronic to silicon and germanium, all of which but AlN have the zinc blende structure.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] All four can be made by high-temperature (and possibly high-pressure) direct reaction of their component elements.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium alloys well with most other metals (with the exception of most alkali metals and group 13 metals) and over 150 intermetallics with other metals are known.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Preparation involves heating fixed metals together in certain proportions, followed by gradual cooling and annealing.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Bonding in them is predominantly metallic and the crystal structure primarily depends on efficiency of packing.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] There are few compounds with lower oxidation states.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Some are aluminium(I) compounds: AlF, AlCl, AlBr, and AlI all exist in the gaseous phase when the respective trihalide is heated with aluminium, and at cryogenic temperatures.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] A stable derivative of aluminium monoiodide is the cyclic adduct formed with triethylamine, Al4I4(NEt3)4.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Al2O and Al2S also exist but are very unstable.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Very simple aluminium(II) compounds are invoked or observed in the reactions of Al metal with oxidants.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] For example, aluminium monoxide, AlO, has been detected in the gas phase after explosion and in stellar absorption spectra.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] More thoroughly investigated are compounds of the formula R4Al2 which contain an Al–Al bond and where R is a large organic ligand.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] A variety of compounds of empirical formula AlR3 and AlR1.5Cl1.5 exist.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The aluminium trialkyls and triaryls are either reactive, volatile, and colorless liquids or low-melting solids.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] They catch fire spontaneously in air and react with water, thus necessitating precautions when handling them.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] They often form dimers, unlike their boron analogues, but this tendency diminishes for branched-chain alkyls (e.g.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] For example, triisobutylaluminium exists as an equilibrium mixture of the monomer and dimer.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] These dimers, such as trimethylaluminium (Al2Me6), usually feature tetrahedral Al centers formed by dimerization with some alkyl group bridging between both aluminium atoms.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] They are hard acids and react readily with ligands, forming adducts.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] In industry, they are mostly used in alkene insertion reactions, as discovered by Karl Ziegler, most importantly in "growth reactions" that form long-chain unbranched primary alkenes and alcohols, and in the low-pressure polymerization of ethene and propene.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] There are also some heterocyclic and cluster organoaluminium compounds involving Al–N bonds.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The industrially most important aluminium hydride is lithium aluminium hydride (LiAlH4), which is used as a reducing agent in organic chemistry.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] It can be produced from lithium hydride and aluminium trichloride.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The simplest hydride, aluminium hydride or alane, is not as important.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] It is a polymer with the formula (AlH3)*n*, which is in contrast to the corresponding boron hydride that is a dimer with the formula (BH3)2.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium's per-particle abundance in the Solar System is 3.15 ppm (parts per million).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] It is the twelfth most abundant of all elements and third most abundant among the elements that have odd atomic numbers, after hydrogen and nitrogen.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The only stable isotope of aluminium, 27Al, is the eighteenth most abundant nucleus in the universe.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] It is created almost entirely after fusion of carbon in massive stars that will later become Type II supernovas: this fusion creates 26Mg, which upon capturing free protons and neutrons, becomes aluminium.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Some smaller quantities of 27Al are created in hydrogen burning shells of evolved stars, where 26Mg can capture free protons.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Essentially all aluminium now in existence is 27Al.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] 26Al was present in the early Solar System with abundance of 0.005% relative to 27Al but its half-life of 728,000 years is too short for any original nuclei to survive; 26Al is therefore extinct.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Unlike for 27Al, hydrogen burning is the primary source of 26Al, with the nuclide emerging after a nucleus of 25Mg catches a free proton.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] However, the trace quantities of 26Al that do exist are the most common gamma ray emitter in the interstellar gas; if the original 26Al were still present, gamma ray maps of the Milky Way would be brighter.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Overall, the Earth is about 1.59% aluminium by mass (seventh in abundance by mass).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium occurs in greater proportion in the Earth's crust than in the universe at large.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] This is because aluminium easily forms the oxide and becomes bound into rocks and stays in the Earth's crust, while less reactive metals sink to the core.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] In the Earth's crust, aluminium is the most abundant metallic element (8.23% by mass) and the third most abundant of all elements (after oxygen and silicon).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] A large number of silicates in the Earth's crust contain aluminium.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] In contrast, the Earth's mantle is only 2.38% aluminium by mass.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium also occurs in seawater at a concentration of 0.41 μg/kg.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Because of its strong affinity for oxygen, aluminium is almost never found in the elemental state; instead it is found in oxides or silicates.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Feldspars, the most common group of minerals in the Earth's crust, are aluminosilicates.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium also occurs in the minerals beryl, cryolite, garnet, spinel, and turquoise.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Impurities in alumina yield gemstones: for example, chromium yields ruby and iron yields sapphire.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Native aluminium metal is extremely rare and can only be found as a minor phase in low oxygen fugacity environments, such as the interiors of certain volcanoes.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Native aluminium has been reported in cold seeps in the northeastern continental slope of the South China Sea.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] It is possible that these deposits resulted from bacterial reduction of tetrahydroxoaluminate Al(OH)4−.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Although aluminium is a common and widespread element, not all aluminium minerals are economically viable sources of the metal.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Almost all metallic aluminium is produced from the ore bauxite (AlO*x*(OH)3–2*x*).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Bauxite occurs as a weathering product of low iron and silica bedrock in tropical climatic conditions.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] In 2017, most bauxite was mined in Australia, China, Guinea, and India.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The history of aluminium has been shaped by usage of alum.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The first written record of alum, made by Greek historian Herodotus, dates back to the 5th century BCE.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The ancients are known to have used alum as a dyeing mordant and for city defense as a fire-resistant coating for wood.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] After the Crusades, alum, an indispensable good in the European fabric industry, was a subject of international commerce; it was imported to Europe from the eastern Mediterranean until the mid-15th century.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The nature of alum remained unknown until Swiss physician Paracelsus suggested alum was a salt of an earth of alum around 1530.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] German doctor and chemist Andreas Libavius experimentally confirmed this in 1595.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] German chemist Friedrich Hoffmann announced his belief that the base of alum was a distinct earth in 1722.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] German chemist Andreas Sigismund Marggraf synthesized alumina in 1754 by boiling clay in sulfuric acid and subsequently adding potash.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Attempts to produce aluminium date back to 1760.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The first successful attempt, however, was completed in 1824 by Danish physicist and chemist Hans Christian Ørsted.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] He reacted anhydrous aluminium chloride with potassium amalgam, yielding a lump of metal looking similar to tin.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] He presented his results and demonstrated a sample of the new metal in 1825.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] In 1827, German chemist Friedrich Wöhler repeated Ørsted's experiments but did not identify any aluminium.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] (The reason for this inconsistency was only discovered in 1921.) He conducted a similar experiment in the same year by mixing anhydrous aluminium chloride with potassium (the Wöhler process) and produced a powder of aluminium.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] In 1845, he was able to produce small pieces of the metal and described some physical properties of this metal.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] For many years thereafter, Wöhler was credited as the discoverer of aluminium.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] As Wöhler's method could not yield great quantities of aluminium, the metal remained rare; its cost exceeded that of gold.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The first industrial production of aluminium was established in 1856 by French chemist Henri Étienne Sainte-Claire Deville and companions.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Sainte-Claire Deville had discovered that aluminium trichloride could be reduced by sodium, which was more convenient and less expensive than potassium, which Wöhler had used.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Even then, aluminium was still not of great purity and produced aluminium differed in properties by sample.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Because of its electricity-conducting capacity, aluminium was used as the cap of the Washington Monument, completed in 1885, the tallest building in the world at the time.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The non-corroding metal cap was intended to serve as a lightning rod peak.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The first industrial large-scale production method was independently developed in 1886 by French engineer Paul Héroult and American engineer Charles Martin Hall; it is now known as the Hall–Héroult process.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The Hall–Héroult process converts alumina into metal.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Austrian chemist Carl Joseph Bayer discovered a way of purifying bauxite to yield alumina, now known as the Bayer process, in 1889.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Modern production of aluminium is based on the Bayer and Hall–Héroult processes.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] As large-scale production caused aluminium prices to drop, the metal became widely used in jewelry, eyeglass frames, optical instruments, tableware, and foil, and other everyday items in the 1890s and early 20th century.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium's ability to form hard yet light alloys with other metals provided the metal with many uses at the time.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] During World War I, major governments demanded large shipments of aluminium for light strong airframes; during World War II, demand by major governments for aviation was even higher.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] From the early 20th century to 1980, the aluminium industry was characterized by cartelization, as aluminium firms colluded to keep prices high and stable.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The first aluminium cartel, the Aluminium Association, was founded in 1901 by the Pittsburgh Reduction Company (renamed Alcoa in 1907) and Aluminium Industrie AG.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The British Aluminium Company, Produits Chimiques d'Alais et de la Camargue, and Société Électro-Métallurgique de Froges also joined the cartel.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] By the mid-20th century, aluminium had become a part of everyday life and an essential component of housewares.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] In 1954, production of aluminium surpassed that of copper, historically second in production only to iron, making it the most produced non-ferrous metal.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] During the mid-20th century, aluminium emerged as a civil engineering material, with building applications in both basic construction and interior finish work, and increasingly being used in military engineering, for both airplanes and armored vehicle engines.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Earth's first artificial satellite, launched in 1957, consisted of two separate aluminium semi-spheres joined and all subsequent space vehicles have used aluminium to some extent.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The aluminium can was invented in 1956 and employed as a storage for drinks in 1958.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Throughout the 20th century, the production of aluminium rose rapidly: while the world production of aluminium in 1900 was 6,800 metric tons, the annual production first exceeded 100,000 metric tons in 1916; 1,000,000 tons in 1941; 10,000,000 tons in 1971.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] In the 1970s, the increased demand for aluminium made it an exchange commodity; it entered the London Metal Exchange, the oldest industrial metal exchange in the world, in 1978.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The output continued to grow: the annual production of aluminium exceeded 50,000,000 metric tons in 2013.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The real price for aluminium declined from $14,000 per metric ton in 1900 to $2,340 in 1948 (in 1998 United States dollars).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Extraction and processing costs were lowered over technological progress and the scale of the economies.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] However, the need to exploit lower-grade poorer quality deposits and the use of fast increasing input costs (above all, energy) increased the net cost of aluminium; the real price began to grow in the 1970s with the rise of energy cost.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Production moved from the industrialized countries to countries where production was cheaper.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Production costs in the late 20th century changed because of advances in technology, lower energy prices, exchange rates of the United States dollar, and alumina prices.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The BRIC countries' combined share in primary production and primary consumption grew substantially in the first decade of the 21st century.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] China is accumulating an especially large share of the world's production thanks to an abundance of resources, cheap energy, and governmental stimuli; it also increased its consumption share from 2% in 1972 to 40% in 2010.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] In the United States, Western Europe, and Japan, most aluminium was consumed in transportation, engineering, construction, and packaging.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] In 2021, prices for industrial metals such as aluminium have soared to near-record levels as energy shortages in China drive up costs for electricity.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The names *aluminium* and *aluminum* are derived from the word *alumine*, an obsolete term for *alumina*, the primary naturally occurring oxide of aluminium.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] *Alumine* was borrowed from French, which in turn derived it from *alumen*, the classical Latin name for alum, the mineral from which it was collected.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The Latin word *alumen* stems from the Proto-Indo-European root **alu-* meaning "bitter" or "beer".
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The English name *alum* does not come directly from Latin, whereas *alumine*/*alumina* comes from the Latin word *alumen* (on declension, *alumen* changes to *alumin-*).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] British chemist Humphry Davy, who performed a number of experiments aimed to isolate the metal, is credited as the person who named the element.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The first name proposed for the metal to be isolated from alum was *alumium*, which Davy suggested in an 1808 article on his electrochemical research, published in Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] It appeared that the name was created from the English word *alum* and the Latin suffix *-ium*; but it was customary then to give elements names originating in Latin, so this name was not adopted universally.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The name *alumium* was criticized by contemporary chemists from France, Germany, and Sweden, who insisted the metal should be named for the oxide, alumina, from which it would be isolated.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] One example was *Essai sur la Nomenclature chimique* (July 1811), written in French by a Swedish chemist, Jöns Jacob Berzelius, in which the name *aluminium* is given to the element that would be synthesized from alum.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] (Another article in the same journal issue also refers to the metal whose oxide is the basis of sapphire, i.e., the same metal, as to *aluminium*.) A January 1811 summary of one of Davy's lectures at the Royal Society mentioned the name *aluminium* as a possibility.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] In 1812, Davy published his chemistry text *Elements of Chemical Philosophy* in which he used the spelling *aluminum*.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] In 1812, British scientist Thomas Young wrote an anonymous review of Davy's book, in which he proposed the name *aluminium* instead of *aluminum*, which he thought had a "less classical sound".
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] This name persisted: although the *-um* spelling was occasionally used in Britain, the American scientific language used *-ium* from the start.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The French have used the spelling *aluminium* from the start.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Most scientists throughout the world used *-ium* in the 19th century; and it was entrenched in several other European languages, such as French, German, and Dutch.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] In 1828, an American lexicographer, Noah Webster, entered only the *aluminum* spelling in his *American Dictionary of the English Language*.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] In the 1830s, the *-um* spelling gained usage in the United States; by the 1860s, it had become the more common spelling there outside science.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] In 1892, Hall used the *-um* spelling in his advertising handbill for his new electrolytic method of producing the metal, despite his constant use of the *-ium* spelling in all the patents he filed between 1886 and 1903.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] It is unknown whether this spelling was introduced by mistake or intentionally, but Hall preferred *aluminum* since its introduction because it resembled *platinum*, the name of a prestigious metal.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] By 1890, both spellings had been common in the United States, the *-ium* spelling being slightly more common; by 1895, the situation had reversed; by 1900, *aluminum* had become twice as common as *aluminium*; in the next decade, the *-um* spelling dominated American usage.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] In 1925, the American Chemical Society adopted the spelling *aluminum*.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC) adopted *aluminium* as the standard international name for the element in 1990.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] In 1993, they recognized *aluminum* as an acceptable variant; the most recent 2005 edition of the IUPAC nomenclature of inorganic chemistry also acknowledges this spelling.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] IUPAC official publications use the *-ium* spelling as primary, and they list both where it is appropriate.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Their usage is currently regional: *aluminum* dominates in the United States and Canada; *aluminium* is prevalent in the rest of the English-speaking world.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] German physicist Ludwig Wilhelm Gilbert had proposed *Thonerde-metall*, after the German *Thonerde* for alumina, in his *Annalen der Physik* but that name never caught on at all even in Germany.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Richards in 1891 found just one occurrence of *argillium* in Swedish, from the French *argille* for clay.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The production of aluminium starts with the extraction of bauxite rock from the ground.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The bauxite is processed and transformed using the Bayer process into alumina, which is then processed using the Hall–Héroult process, resulting in the final aluminium.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium production is highly energy-consuming, and so the producers tend to locate smelters in places where electric power is both plentiful and inexpensive.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Production of one kilogram of aluminium requires 7 kilograms of oil energy equivalent, as compared to 1.5 kilograms for steel and 2 kilograms for plastic.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] As of 2024, the world's largest producers of aluminium were China, India, Russia, Canada, and the United Arab Emirates, while China is by far the top producer of aluminium with a world share of over 55%.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] According to the International Resource Panel's Metal Stocks in Society report, the global per capita stock of aluminium in use in society (i.e. in cars, buildings, electronics, etc.) is 80 kg (180 lb).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Much of this is in more-developed countries (350–500 kg (770–1,100 lb) per capita) rather than less-developed countries (35 kg (77 lb) per capita).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Bauxite is converted to alumina by the Bayer process.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Bauxite is blended for uniform composition and then is ground fine.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] After this reaction, the slurry is at a temperature above its atmospheric boiling point.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] It is cooled by removing steam as pressure is reduced.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The bauxite residue is separated from the solution and discarded.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The solution, free of solids, is seeded with small crystals of aluminium hydroxide; this causes decomposition of the [Al(OH)4]− ions to aluminium hydroxide.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] After about half of aluminium has precipitated, the mixture is sent to classifiers.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Small crystals of aluminium hydroxide are collected to serve as seeding agents; coarse particles are converted to alumina by heating; the excess solution is removed by evaporation, (if needed) purified, and recycled.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The conversion of alumina to aluminium is achieved by the Hall–Héroult process.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] In this energy-intensive process, a solution of alumina in a molten (940 and 970 °C (1,720 and 1,780 °F)) mixture of cryolite (Na3AlF6) with calcium fluoride is electrolyzed to produce metallic aluminium.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The liquid aluminium sinks to the bottom of the solution and is tapped off, and usually cast into large blocks called aluminium billets for further processing.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Anodes of the electrolysis cell are made of carbon—the most resistant material against fluoride corrosion—and either bake at the process or are prebaked.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The former, also called Söderberg anodes, are less power-efficient and fumes released during baking are costly to collect, which is why they are being replaced by prebaked anodes even though they save the power, energy, and labor to prebake the cathodes.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Carbon for anodes should be preferably pure so that neither aluminium nor the electrolyte is contaminated with ash.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Despite carbon's resistivity against corrosion, it is still consumed at a rate of 0.4–0.5 kg per each kilogram of produced aluminium.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Cathodes are made of anthracite; high purity for them is not required because impurities leach only very slowly.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The cathode is consumed at a rate of 0.02–0.04 kg per each kilogram of produced aluminium.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] A cell is usually terminated after 2–6 years following a failure of the cathode.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The Hall–Heroult process produces aluminium with a purity of above 99%.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Further purification can be done by the Hoopes process.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] This process involves the electrolysis of molten aluminium with a sodium, barium, and aluminium fluoride electrolyte.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The resulting aluminium has a purity of 99.99%.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Electric power represents about 20 to 40% of the cost of producing aluminium, depending on the location of the smelter.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium production consumes roughly 5% of electricity generated in the United States.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Because of this, alternatives to the Hall–Héroult process have been researched, but none has turned out to be economically feasible.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Recovery of the metal through recycling has become an important task of the aluminium industry.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Recycling was a low-profile activity until the late 1960s, when the growing use of aluminium beverage cans brought it to public awareness.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Recycling involves melting the scrap, a process that requires only 5% of the energy used to produce aluminium from ore, though a significant part (up to 15% of the input material) is lost as dross (ash-like oxide).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] An aluminium stack melter produces significantly less dross, with values reported below 1%.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] White dross from primary aluminium production and from secondary recycling operations still contains useful quantities of aluminium that can be extracted industrially.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The process produces aluminium billets, together with a highly complex waste material.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] It reacts with water, releasing a mixture of gases including, among others, acetylene, hydrogen sulfide and significant amounts of ammonia.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Despite these difficulties, the waste is used as a filler in asphalt and concrete.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Its potential for hydrogen production has also been considered and researched.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The global production of aluminium in 2016 was 58.8 million metric tons.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] It exceeded that of any other metal except iron (1,231 million metric tons).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is almost always alloyed, which markedly improves its mechanical properties, especially when tempered.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] For example, the common aluminium foils and beverage cans are alloys of 92% to 99% aluminium.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The main alloying agents for both wrought and cast aluminium are copper, zinc, magnesium, manganese, and silicon (e.g., duralumin) with the levels of other metals in a few percent by weight.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium is the main substitute to copper and its applications to the traditional domains of copper have seen increased interest when copper prices are high such as in 2011–2014 and 2021.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] There is a competition in the use of aluminium and copper in the automotive industry, but in other uses such as in the construction industry and in underground and submarine cables aluminium has been largely unable to compete with copper.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The great majority (about 90%) of aluminium oxide is converted to metallic aluminium.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Being a very hard material (Mohs hardness 9), alumina is widely used as an abrasive; being extraordinarily chemically inert, it is useful in highly reactive environments such as high pressure sodium lamps.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium oxide is commonly used as a catalyst for industrial processes; e.g. the Claus process to convert hydrogen sulfide to sulfur in refineries and to alkylate amines.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Many industrial catalysts are supported by alumina, meaning that the expensive catalyst material is dispersed over a surface of the inert alumina.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Another principal use is as a drying agent or absorbent.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Several sulfates of aluminium have industrial and commercial application.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium sulfate (in its hydrate form) is produced on the annual scale of several millions of metric tons.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] About two-thirds is consumed in water treatment.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] The next major application is in the manufacture of paper.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] It is also used as a mordant in dyeing, in pickling seeds, deodorizing of mineral oils, in leather tanning, and in production of other aluminium compounds.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Two kinds of alum, ammonium alum and potassium alum, were formerly used as mordants and in leather tanning, but their use has significantly declined following availability of high-purity aluminium sulfate.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Anhydrous aluminium chloride is used as a catalyst in chemical and petrochemical industries, the dyeing industry, and in synthesis of various inorganic and organic compounds.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Aluminium hydroxychlorides are used in purifying water, in the paper industry, and as antiperspirants.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p01] Sodium aluminate is used in treating water and as an accelerator of solidification of cement.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p02] Despite its widespread occurrence in the Earth's crust, aluminium has no known function in biology.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p02] At pH 6–9 (relevant for most natural waters), aluminium precipitates out of water as the hydroxide and is hence not available; most elements behaving this way have no biological role or are toxic.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p02] Aluminium sulfate has an LD50 of 6207 mg/kg (oral, mouse).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p02] Aluminium is classified as a non-carcinogen by the United States Department of Health and Human Services.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p02] A review published in 1988 said that there was little evidence that normal exposure to aluminium presents a risk to healthy adult, and a 2014 multi-element toxicology review was unable to find deleterious effects of aluminium consumed in amounts not greater than 40 mg/day per kg of body mass.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p02] Most ingested aluminium is eliminated in feces, and much of what enters the bloodstream is excreted in urine; however, not all absorbed or parenterally administered aluminium is cleared through urinary excretion.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p02] Aluminium, although rarely, can cause vitamin D-resistant osteomalacia, erythropoietin-resistant microcytic anemia, and central nervous system alterations.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p02] People with kidney insufficiency are especially at a risk.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p02] Chronic ingestion of hydrated aluminium silicates (for excess gastric acidity control) may result in aluminium binding to intestinal contents and increased elimination of other metals, such as iron or zinc; sufficiently high doses (>50 g/day) can cause anemia.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p02] During the 1988 Camelford water pollution incident, people in Camelford had their drinking water contaminated with aluminium sulfate for several weeks.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p02] A final report into the incident in 2013 concluded it was unlikely that this had caused long-term health problems.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p02] Aluminium has been suspected of being a possible cause of Alzheimer's disease, but research into this for over 40 years has found, as of 2018, no good evidence of causal effect.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p02] Aluminium increases estrogen-related gene expression in human breast cancer cells cultured in the laboratory.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p02] In very high doses, aluminium is associated with altered function of the blood–brain barrier.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p02] A small percentage of people have contact allergies to aluminium and experience itchy red rashes, headache, muscle pain, joint pain, poor memory, insomnia, depression, asthma, irritable bowel syndrome, or other symptoms upon contact with products containing aluminium.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p02] Exposure to powdered aluminium or aluminium welding fumes can cause pulmonary fibrosis.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p02] Fine aluminium powder can ignite or explode, posing another workplace hazard.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p02] Drinking water contains more aluminium than solid food; however, aluminium in food may be absorbed more than aluminium from water.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p02] Dietary exposure in Europeans averages to 0.2–1.5 mg/kg/week but can be as high as 2.3 mg/kg/week.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p02] Higher exposure levels of aluminium are mostly limited to plumbers, masons, electrical workers, machinists, and surgeons.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p02] Consumption of antacids, antiperspirants, vaccines, and cosmetics provide possible routes of exposure.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p02] Consumption of acidic foods or liquids with aluminium enhances aluminium absorption, and maltol has been shown to increase the accumulation of aluminium in nerve and bone tissues.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p02] In case of suspected sudden intake of a large amount of aluminium, the only treatment is deferoxamine mesylate which may be given to help eliminate aluminium from the body by chelation therapy.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p02] However, this should be applied with caution as this reduces not only aluminium body levels, but also those of other metals such as copper or iron.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p02] High levels of aluminium occur near mining sites; small amounts of aluminium are released to the environment at coal-fired power plants or incinerators.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p02] Aluminium in the air is washed out by the rain or normally settles down but small particles of aluminium remain in the air for a long time.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p02] Acidic precipitation is the main natural factor to mobilize aluminium from natural sources and the main reason for the environmental effects of aluminium; however, the main factor of presence of aluminium in salt and freshwater are the industrial processes that also release aluminium into air.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p02] In water, aluminium acts as a toxic agent on gill-breathing animals such as fish when the water is acidic, in which aluminium may precipitate on gills, which causes loss of plasma- and hemolymph ions leading to osmoregulatory failure.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p02] Organic complexes of aluminium may be easily absorbed and interfere with metabolism in mammals and birds, even though this rarely happens in practice.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p02] Aluminium is primary among the factors that reduce plant growth on acidic soils.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p02] Although it is generally harmless to plant growth in pH-neutral soils, in acid soils the concentration of toxic Al3+ cations increases and disturbs root growth and function.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p02] Wheat has developed a tolerance to aluminium, releasing organic compounds that bind to harmful aluminium cations.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p02] Sorghum is believed to have the same tolerance mechanism.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p02] Aluminium production possesses its own challenges to the environment on each step of the production process.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p02] The major challenge is the emission of greenhouse gases.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p02] These gases result from electrical consumption of the smelters and the byproducts of processing.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p02] The most potent of these gases are perfluorocarbons, namely CF4 and C2F6, from the smelting process.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p02] Biodegradation of metallic aluminium is extremely rare; most aluminium-corroding organisms do not directly attack or consume the aluminium, but instead produce corrosive wastes.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p02] The fungus *Geotrichum candidum* can consume the aluminium in compact discs.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/aluminum-p02] The bacterium *Pseudomonas aeruginosa* and the fungus *Cladosporium resinae* are commonly detected in aircraft fuel tanks that use kerosene-based fuels (not avgas), and laboratory cultures can degrade aluminium.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] The **AMC straight-6 engine** is a family of straight-six engines produced by American Motors Corporation (AMC) and used in passenger cars and Jeep vehicles from 1964 through 2006.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] Production continued after Chrysler acquired AMC in 1987.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] American Motors continued to use the Rambler straight-six engine initially designed by Nash Motors.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] It was redesigned as an OHV for the 1956 model year.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] American Motors introduced a completely new I6 design in 1964.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] This engine evolved in several displacements and underwent upgrades.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] Vehículos Automotores Mexicanos (VAM) also manufactured this family of six-cylinder engines, including two versions available only in Mexico.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] A new 4.0 L engine was introduced by AMC in 1986 for the 1987 model year Jeep Cherokee (XJ) and became the final version of AMC's inline sixes.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] It is regarded as one of the best 4x4 and off-road engines.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] This engine was produced by Chrysler through 2006.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] Among "classic American engines, the AMC straight-six stands as a testament to smart engineering and enduring performance".
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] The straight-six engine lineage at AMC goes back to Nash Motors.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] An economy-focused engine debuted in the 1941 Nash Ambassador 600 model.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] Its initial displacement of 172.6 cu in (2.8 L) was subsequently increased to 184 cu in (3.0 L) and finally to 195.6 cu in (3.2 L) in 1952.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] After Nash merged with Hudson to form AMC in 1954, efforts continued to enhance performance and meet evolving market demands.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] The engine's architecture underwent a significant transformation for the 1956 model year, transitioning from a flathead (L-head) side-valve configuration to an overhead valve (OHV) design.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] This modernization aimed to improve engine efficiency and power output.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] The flathead version was reintroduced in 1958, serving as the base economy engine for the newly launched Rambler American compact car.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] This dual-engine strategy persisted until 1965, catering to performance-oriented and economy-minded consumers.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] To reduce vehicle weight and enhance fuel efficiency, AMC introduced a die-cast aluminum block version of the OHV 195.6 cu in (3.2 L) engine in 1961.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] This innovative approach resulted in a significant weight reduction, with the aluminum engine weighing 380 lb (170 kg), compared to its cast-iron counterpart's 460 lb (210 kg).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] This aluminum engine was produced through 1964, showcasing AMC's engineering prowess and willingness to experiment with advanced materials.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] While not known for high performance, this engine was known for reliability.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] This engine was also used in marine applications.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] American Motors introduced a groundbreaking inline-six engine in 1964.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] It featured a short-stroke design and a robust seven-main bearing crankshaft with an overall design to provide good torque at low RPMs.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] This engine, a testament to AMC's engineering, enjoyed a remarkable production run that continued under AMC and Vehículos Automotores Mexicanos (VAM) as well as by Chrysler until 2006.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] Its enduring legacy and reputation as a reliable and rugged engine, particularly in off-road applications, has solidified its position as superior to Chrysler's Slant-6.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] Initially marketed as the "Torque Command" engine, the 232 cu in (3.8 L) inline-six represented AMC's first genuinely modern six-cylinder engine.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] To commemorate the engine's launch in May 1964, AMC produced 2,520 special "Typhoon" editions based on the Rambler Classic two-door hardtop.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] These distinctive vehicles featured the 145 hp (108 kW; 147 PS) 8.5:1 compression ratio engine, a striking Solar Yellow exterior with a Classic Black roof, and "Typhoon" badging in place of the standard "Classic" script.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] Notably, all other Rambler Classic options, except alternative engine choices, were available on the Typhoon edition.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] For the 1965 model year, the 232 engine superseded the aging Nash 195.6 cu in (3.2 L) OHV inline-six in the Classic and Ambassador models.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] This marked the return of a six-cylinder engine in the Ambassador line since 1956, reflecting AMC's commitment to offering a wider range of powertrain options.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] In 1966, AMC expanded its six-cylinder lineup by introducing the 199 cu in (3.3 L) version of the 232 engine.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] This smaller variant replaced the OHV and L-head 195.6 cu in (3.2 L) engines across AMC's passenger car lineup.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] Both the 199 and 232 engines shared a 3.75 in (95.3 mm) bore, differing only in stroke: 3 in (76.2 mm) for the 199 and 3.5 in (88.9 mm) for the 232.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] The 199 engine was discontinued in 1970, while the 232 continued production alongside the larger 258 cu in (4.2 L) engine, which the increase in displacement was achieved by employing a 3.895 in (98.9 mm) stroke crankshaft and a slightly taller engine block.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] More stringent emission control regulations, coupled with the growing weight of vehicles due to safety mandates, led to a gradual decline in engine power output, ultimately resulting in the discontinuation of the 232 in 1979.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] The 199 cu in (3.3 L) engine was produced from 1965 through 1970.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] Rated at 128 hp (95 kW; 130 PS) @ 4400 rpm and 182 lb⋅ft (247 N⋅m) of torque @ 1600 rpm, it was the standard engine beginning with the compact 1966 Rambler American series.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] Barney Navarro selected the 199 AMC engine to power a race car for the Indianapolis 500.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] This engine had not been used in an IndyCar.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] However, Navarro selected it "due both to its strong bottom end and thick cylinder walls." For the first Indy attempt, Navarro designed a fuel-injection system, a unique head, and a single turbo to achieve 550 hp (410 kW; 558 PS) at 6000 rpm.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] This was with the stock block featuring seven main bearings and large journal sizes, while the second block was drilled for four-bolt caps.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] Successive engines incorporated double turbochargers to produce 640–700 hp (477–522 kW; 649–710 PS).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] Navarro fielded a 1964 Watson car with the AMC 199 engine for three years at the Indianapolis 500.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] However, the #50 Navarro-Rambler never qualified due to problems with drivers and with the suspension of the cars.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] The car was also entered at the 1971 IndyCar "Rafaela 300" season opener in Argentina.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] This was the car's fourth actual race start, and it began at 19 on the starting grid.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] This car was then driven by Les Scott in practice for the 1971 Indy 500 race.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] The following year, another attempt to qualify was with Leon Sirois as the driver.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] An auction was held on 14 July 2005, to clear the remaining contents of the Navarro Engineering shop in Los Angeles.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] A private collector purchased a complete Navarro 700 hp (522 kW; 710 PS) 199 cu in (3.3 L) engine for $15,000.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] The 232 cu in (3.8 L) engine was produced from 1964 until 1979.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] The 232 was the base six-cylinder engine on many models through 1979, and even towards the end of its usage, it was considered reasonably modern in design.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] After its midyear 1964 introduction in the "Typhoon" two-door hardtop as part of the mid-sized Rambler Classic line, the 232 engine was adapted to fit into the smaller 1965 Rambler American by using a special short water pump, an adaptive piece also used in the 1971 through 1975 Jeep CJ-5.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] Air conditioning was available only with the older 196 engine in the American models because there was not enough space for the compressor with the longer 232.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] Through the 1970 model year, the 232 shared a deck height with the 199 cu in (3.3 L) engines.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] Starting in 1971, AMC raised the deck height to produce the 258, and the 232 adopted the 199's longer connecting rods and shared deck height with the 258.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] In 1972, the bell housing bolt pattern changed to match the larger version used on the V8 engines.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] Changes for the 1976 model year included fuel economy improvements that reduced emissions and warmup time.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] This was accomplished by reshaped carburetor air passages that pushed the fuel efficiency of a 232-equipped AMC Gremlin to 30 mpg‑US (7.8 L/100 km; 36 mpg‑imp) as tested by the United States Environmental Protection Agency, compared to 24 mpg‑US (9.8 L/100 km; 29 mpg‑imp) in 1975.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] The 252 cu in (4.1 L) engine was produced by AMC's Mexican subsidiary Vehículos Automotores Mexicanos (VAM) beginning in 1969 and was dropped after 1972, replaced with AMC's 258 for the 1973 model year onward.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] This was similar to a 232 in stroke with a larger 3.91 in (99.3 mm) bore, for an actual displacement of 252.15 cu in (4.1 L).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] It was produced in VAM's Lerma, Estado de México engine plant.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] It featured an undersquare 3.75 in (95.3 mm) bore and 3.895 in (98.9 mm) stroke; it was otherwise similar to the 199 and 232 (Note: Starting in the mid-1970s the 258's bore and stroke was changed to a 3.82 in (97 mm) bore over a 3.75" stroke.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] This allowed one block to be used for both the 232 and 258 and the same crankshaft blank could be milled to the two different strokes).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] This engine is considered reliable, inexpensive, and torquey.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] For 1981, as part of a weight reduction program (aluminum intake manifold, plastic rocker arm cover), the crankshaft was changed from a twelve counterweight design to four, saving approximately 20 pounds (9.1 kg).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] This engine also found use in farm/industrial applications such as the International Harvester 4000 swather.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] The 282 cu in (4.6 L) engine was produced by AMC's Mexican subsidiary Vehículos Automotores Mexicanos (VAM) beginning in 1971 through 1986.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] This was similar to a 258 in stroke, cast with a larger 3.917 in (99.5 mm) bore, 0.16 in (4.1 mm) larger than the 258, making 281.7 cu in (4.6 L).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] All VAM 282s from 1971 through 1978 were still advertised with an output measured using the gross rating system that was last used under AMC in 1971.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] The 1979 through 1983 engines were measured under the new net rating system.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] All units were produced in VAM's engine plant located in Lerma, Estado de México.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] A high-performance version was developed by VAM, derived from the racing team engine.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] The modifications consisted of headers, 302 degree camshaft, semi-ported cylinder heads, modified electronic distributor, aluminium intake manifold, a Holley 2300 350CFM carburettor, reinforced harmonic damper, and a heavy duty cooling system (larger capacity radiator and fan clutch).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] The 282, which had a larger bore, is considered the ancestor of the L stroker engine, where it is common for the engine rebuilder to use an AMC 258 crankshaft in a Jeep 4.0 cylinder block – a 4.5 uses the stock AMC 258 connecting rods (with stock or .020 overbore using aftermarket pistons).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] In contrast, the 4.6, 4.7, and 5.0 strokers use the 258 cranks, but retain the 4.0 connecting rods.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] American Motors began developing the 242 cu in (4.0 L) engine in 1984 and it was completed in just 26 months using many off-the-shelf components while featuring, among others, additional strength, improved combustion chamber, port setup, and cam profile.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] The total weight of the new engine was 483 pounds (219 kg), only one pound more than the 258 six despite its heavier-duty components and parts.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] The cast aluminum valve cover featured 15 bolts, the industry's most, to achieve a positive seal.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] The new engine, which was introduced in 1986 for the 1987 model year, was a further evolution of AMC's 258 six.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] The new 4.0 L was not a re-bored version of the 4.2 as AMC engineers modified the 258's architecture.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] However, they incorporated elements from the 2.5 L four-cylinder engine introduced in 1984 which utilized the valvetrain of the 258 (minus cylinders two and five) and performance enhancements because of I4's new block, head, and crank.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] The new 4.0 L featured a 3.875 in (98.4 mm) bore and a 3.414 in (86.7 mm) stroke giving it a displacement of 241.6 cu in (4.0 L).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] Connecting rod length was 6.125 inches — similar to the discontinued 199 which was phased out in 1970.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] The 4.0 L is one of AMC's best-known engines.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] It was one of four AMC engines kept in production when Chrysler bought AMC in 1987.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] Chrysler engineers continued to refine the engine to reduce noise, vibration, and harshness.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] The last in the line of the AMC inline sixes, the 4.0 L is regarded as one of the best Chrysler 4x4 off-road engines.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] The vibration dampener (harmonic balancer) usually gives out after 300,000 miles, where it is common for the rubber insulation to deteriorate where a service replacement is warranted.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] The 4.0 "has a very good reputation for dependability and durability.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] When introduced, the block-mounted oil filter check valve was eliminated on the 4.0 (along with the 2.5 and 4.2 L engines manufactured after September 1986) when AMC engineers standardized their oil filters.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] The pre-1987 engines had an oil filter adapter with 3/4 (cylinder block end) and 13/16 threads (which used a GM oil filter common to Buick, Oldsmobile, Pontiac, and Cadillac V8 engines).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] In contrast, the 1987 through 1990 engines were fitted with a M20x1.5 metric thread filter.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] This was revised in 1991 to the common 3/4 threaded Mopar and Ford V8 oil filter; the oil filter adapter was redesigned where the oil filter is positioned 90 degrees offset adjacent to the starter motor — a Ford V8 oil filter can be used in place of the short filter increasing filter capacity.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] The first 4.0 L engines in 1987 had a Renix (Renault/Bendix) engine management system considered quite advanced for their time.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] A knock sensor allowed the ECU to control spark advance in response to fuel octane and engine load.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] Unfortunately, few scan tools can interface with the system to pull diagnostic codes.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] The RENIX systems also have no permanent memory for diagnostic codes, thus making diagnosing intermittent problems more challenging.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] In 1991, a Chrysler multi-port fuel injection system replaced the RENIX system, and the intake ports were raised approximately 1⁄8 in (3.2 mm) for a better entry radius.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] Chrysler also enlarged the throttle body and redesigned the intake and exhaust manifolds for more efficiency, and the fuel injectors were replaced with higher flow units.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] The net result was an engine that made 190 hp (142 kW; 193 PS) and 225 lb⋅ft (305 N⋅m).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] Badging on most Jeeps equipped with this engine reads "4.0 Litre HIGH OUTPUT." The new cam profile combined with altered computer programming eliminated the need for an EGR valve and knock sensor, but made the engine more sensitive to alterations, especially where emissions are concerned.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] The OEM fuel injectors used with the Mopar MPI system (manufactured by Siemens) have been known to leak fuel especially with OBD-II where plugged catalytic converters are common which usually throws a P0420 code.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] Minor changes were made to the cylinder head for the 1995 model year.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] In 1996, the engine block was redesigned for greater strength.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] The new block had more webbing and a stud girdle for added rigidity of the crankshaft main bearings.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] Engines installed in 1999 Grand Cherokees carried the "PowerTech" name that had been used intermittently in prior years and on other Chrysler truck and SUV engines.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] The name was subsequently passed on to 4.0s in the other Jeep models that used the engine, the Cherokee and Wrangler.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] The cylinder head was again changed for the 2000 model year to a more emissions-friendly design.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] This head was designated as "0331" in the casting number.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] Early 0331 heads are prone to cracking, causing coolant to contaminate the oil, which can lead to catastrophic engine failure.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] The head cracks in the center between #3 and #4 cylinders.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] The crack is usually discernible with the valve cover removed as a "milky" tan line.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] This condition is usually discovered before a catastrophic engine failure, but can lead there if not corrected promptly.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] A new casting was introduced to fix the issue in late 2001, but the same casting number was retained.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] The "fixed" heads have "TUPY" cast in the center where the cracks used to occur.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] Despite the new casting having a better reputation than the earlier 0331 heads, it is not unheard of for the same crack to occur on a TUPY marked cylinder head.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] Also new for the 2000 model year, was the distributor-less, coil on plug ignition system.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] The 4.0 L engine was discontinued at the end of the 2006 model year, replaced in the redesigned 2007 JK Jeep Wrangler by Chrysler's 3.8 L OHV V6, which originated in the company's minivans.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] The deck height of the AMC six-cylinder block was increased by 1⁄8 in (3.2 mm) (half the rod length difference) in 1971 to allow for the longer stroke required for the 258.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] Tall is from 1974 through 1976 AMC factory service manuals; before 1974, deck height was not printed.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] Deck heights may have changed to accommodate slightly different compression ratios over the years.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] The 1971 and older blocks use a "small" bell housing bolt pattern exclusive to AMC and small Nash sixes.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] In 1972, the bell housing bolt pattern was changed to match the AMC V8s.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] Its final use was in 2006 when the 4.0 L was phased out.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] Four bolts on the cylinder block are matched to the transmission bell housing where an adapter plate serves as a dust cover — two additional bolt holes on the transmission bellhousing used on the AMC V8 are used to secure the dust cover.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/amc-straight-6-engine] The 1971 model year 258 uses the "small" pattern, the only version of the 258 to do so.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors' most similar competitors were those automakers that held similar annual sales levels, such as Studebaker, Packard, Kaiser Motors, and Willys-Overland.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Their largest competitors were the Big Three—Ford, General Motors, and Chrysler.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] After periods of intermittent independent success, Renault acquired a significant interest in American Motors in 1979, and the company was ultimately acquired by Chrysler in 1987.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] In January 1954, Nash-Kelvinator Corporation began the acquisition of the Hudson Motor Car Company (in what was called a merger).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The new corporation would be called the American Motors Corporation.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] An earlier corporation with the same name, co-founded by Louis Chevrolet, had existed in Plainfield, New Jersey, from 1916 through 1922 before merging into the Bessemer–American Motors Corporation.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The new company retained Hudson CEO A.E.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Barit as a consultant and he took a seat on the board of directors.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Mason, the architect of the merger, believed that the survival of the U.S.'s remaining independent automakers depended on their joining to form one multiple-brand company capable of challenging the Big Three as an equal.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The "frantic 1953–54 Ford/GM price war" devastated the remaining "independent" automakers.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The reasons for the merger between Nash and Hudson included helping cut costs and strengthen their sales organizations to meet the intense competition expected from autos' Big Three.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] One quick result from the merger was the doubling up with Nash on purchasing and production, allowing Hudson to cut prices an average of $155 on the Wasp line, and up to $204 on the more expensive Hornet models.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] After the merger, AMC had its first profitable quarter during the second three months of 1955, earning $1,592,307, compared to a loss of $3,848,667 during the same period in the previous year.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Mason also entered into informal discussions with James J.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Nance of Packard to outline his strategic vision.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Interim plans were made for American Motors to buy Packard Ultramatic automatic transmissions and Packard V8 engines for certain American Motors products.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] In July 1954, Packard acquired Studebaker.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The new Studebaker-Packard Corporation (S-P) made the new 320 cu in (5.2 L) Packard V8 engine and Packard's Ultramatic automatic transmission available to American Motors for its 1955 Nash Ambassador and Hudson Hornet models.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Ironically, Romney had once been offered Nance's job.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1948, Romney received offers from Packard for the post of chief operating officer and from Nash for the number two position in the company.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Although the Packard offer would have paid more, Romney decided to work under Mason because he thought Nash had a brighter future.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Mason and Nance had agreed that S-P would endeavor to purchase parts from American Motors in return, but S-P did not do so.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] As the Packard engines and transmissions were comparatively expensive, American Motors began development of its own V8.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors also spent US$40 million developing its Double Safe Single Unit monocoque, which debuted in the 1956 model year.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] In mid-1956, the 352 cu in (5.8 L) Packard V8 and TwinUltramatic transmission were phased out and replaced by American Motors's new V8 and by GM Hydra-Matic and Borg-Warner transmissions.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors combined the Nash and Hudson product lines under a common manufacturing strategy in 1955, with the production of Nashes and Hudsons consolidated at the Nash plant in Kenosha.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Detroit Hudson plant was converted to military contract production and eventually sold.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The separate Nash and Hudson dealer networks were retained.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Hudsons were redesigned to harmonize with Nash's body styles.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The fast-selling Nash Rambler model was sold as a Nash and a Hudson in 1955 and 1956.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] These badge-engineered Ramblers, and similarly the small Metropolitans, were identical except for the hubcaps, nameplates, and other minor trim.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The pre-existing full-size Nash product line was continued with the Nash Statesman restyled as the "new" Hudson Wasp and the Nash Ambassador restyled as the Hudson Hornet.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Although the cars shared the same body shell, they were at least as different from one another as Chevrolet and Pontiac.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Hudsons and Nashes each used their engines as they had previously: the Hudson Hornet continued to offer the 308 cu in (5.0 L) I6 that had powered the (NASCAR) champion during the early 1950s; the Wasp now used the former engine of the Hudson Jet.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Nash Ambassador and Statesman continued with overhead- valve and L-head sixes, respectively.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Hudson and Nash cars had different front suspensions.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Trunk lids were interchangeable, but other body panels, rear window glass, dash panels, and braking systems differed.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Hudson Hornet, Wasp, and their Nash counterparts had improved ride, visibility, and fuel economy because of their lighter unitized Nash body.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The larger Nash and Hudson range did not sell well, and AMC lost money each year.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Dismayed with the results, Romney decided in 1956 that the company's future lay with the compact Rambler line.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Romney halted production on the new large cars and focused entirely on the new Rambler Six and V8 introducing them in 1956, despite being scheduled for a 1957 release.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Sales of the new Ramblers were poor, and sales of the Hudson and Nash models were almost non-existent, resulting in a $31.7 million operating loss for 1956.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Sales improved in 1957, but the company saw a $11.8 million loss.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] In response, Romney launched a massive public relations campaign, traveling 70,000 miles (112,654 kilometres) nationwide in 12 months.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Romney spoke at union halls, dinners, churches, fairgrounds, and radio and TV stations.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] He was anywhere where he could get the word out about Rambler.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Rambler sales took off in 1958, up 58.7%, and 425 new dealers were signed up.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] As a result, 1958 became AMC's first year of profitability since its formation, with $28 million in earnings.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Nash and Hudson brands were dropped, and Rambler became a marque in its own right and the mainstay of the company.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The popular British-built Metropolitan subcompact continued as a standalone brand until it was discontinued in 1961.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The prototype 1958 Nash Ambassador/Hudson Hornet, built on a stretched Rambler platform, was renamed at the last minute as "Ambassador by Rambler".
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] To round out the model line, American Motors reintroduced the previous 1955, 100 in (2,540 mm) wheelbase Nash Rambler as the new Rambler American with only a few modifications.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] This gave Rambler a compact lineup that included the reintroduced American, the 108 in (2,743 mm) wheelbase Rambler Six and Rebel V8, as well as the 117 in (2,972 mm) wheelbase Ambassador.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Sales of Ramblers soared in the late 1950s partly because of American Motors' focus on the compact car and its marketing efforts.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] These included sponsoring the hugely popular Walt Disney anthology television series and as an exhibitor at the Disneyland theme park in Anaheim, California.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] George Romney himself pitched the Rambler product in television commercials.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] While the "Big Three" introduced ever-larger cars, American Motors followed a "dinosaur-fighter" strategy.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Romney's leadership focused the company on the compact car, a fuel-efficient vehicle 20 years before there was a real need for them.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] This gave Romney a high profile in the media.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Two core strategic factors came into play: (1) the use of shared components in American Motors products and (2) a refusal to participate in the Big Three's restyling race.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] This cost-control policy helped Rambler develop a reputation for building solid economy cars.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Company officials were confident in the changing market and in 1959 announced a $10 million (US$110,445,205 today) expansion of its Kenosha complex (to increase annual straight-time capacity from 300,000 to 440,000 cars).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors was also beginning to experiment with non-gasoline-powered automobiles.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] On April 1, 1959, American Motors and Sonotone Corporation announced a joint research effort to consider producing an electric car that was to be powered by a "self-charging" battery.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Sonotone had the technology for making sintered plate nickel–cadmium batteries that can be recharged very rapidly and are lighter than a typical automobile lead–acid battery.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1959, American Motors hired designer Dick Teague, who had previously worked for General Motors, Packard, and Chrysler; after Edmund E.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Anderson left the company in 1961, Teague was named principal designer and in 1964, vice president.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] To stay competitive, American Motors produced a wide range of products during the 1960s and added innovations long before the "Big Three" introduced them.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] For example, the Rambler Classic was equipped with a standard tandem master cylinder in 1962 that provided stopping ability even if there was a failure in the brake system.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Only Cadillac also included this safety feature six years before U.S. safety regulations required it on all cars.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] S. automotive industry, American Motors offered adjustable front seat backrests from their Nash-origin, and in 1964, the Classic and Ambassador were equipped with standard dual reclining front seats nearly a decade before the Big Three offered them as options.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Bendix disc brakes were made standard on the Marlin and optional on other models in 1965.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] This made the Marlin one of the first modern American cars with standard disc brakes, while the Big Three did not offer them until the early 1970s on most of their models to meet Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standards.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] In the early part of the decade, sales were strong, thanks in no small part to the company's history of building small cars, which came into vogue in 1961.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] In both 1960 and 1961, Ramblers ranked in third place among U.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] S. automobile sales, up from third on the strength of small-car sales, even in the face of a lot of new competition.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Romney's strategic focus was very successful, as reflected in the firm's healthy profits year after year.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The company became completely debt-free.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The financial success allowed the company to reach an agreement on August 26, 1961, with the United Auto Workers for a profit sharing plan that was new in the automobile industry.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Its new three-year labor contract included generous annual improvement pay increases, and automatic cost-of-living raises.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] However, in 1962, Romney resigned to run for Governor of Michigan.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] His replacement was Roy Abernethy, American Motors' successful sales executive.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] By 1964, Studebaker production in the United States had ended, and its Canadian operations ceased in 1966.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The "Big Three", plus the smaller American Motors, Kaiser Jeep, International Harvester, Avanti, and Checker companies were the remaining North American auto manufacturers.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Abernethy believed that American Motors's reputation of building reliable, economical cars could translate into a new strategy that could follow AMC buyers as they traded into larger, more expensive vehicles.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors, in reality, had produced large cars throughout its history.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Rambler Ambassadors were as large as a full-sized Ford or Chevy.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] There was only an absence of largest-sized cars from the American Motors lineup in 1963 and 1964 The first cars bearing his signature were the 1965 models.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The 1965 models were a major makeover of the new platform that had just been introduced in 1963.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] These were a longer Ambassador series and new convertibles for the larger models.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] During mid-year, a fastback, called the Marlin, was added.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] It competed directly with cars like the Dodge Charger, but AMC's "family-sized" fastback emphasized personal-luxury.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The continuing quest "in the business world's toughest race – the grinding contest against the Big Three automobile makers" also meant annual styling changes requiring large expenditures.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors's management total confidence "that the new 1965 models would stem a bothersome decline" actually began falling behind in share of sales.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Moreover, a new line of redesigned cars in the full and mid-sized markets was launched in the fall of 1966.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The cars won acclaim for their fluid styling, and Abernethy's ideas did work as Ambassador sales increased significantly.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] However, the dated designs of the Rambler Americans hurt its sales, which offset gains from Ambassador sales.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] There were quality control problems with introducing the new full-sized cars and persistent rumors of the company's demise because of its precarious cash flow.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Consumer Reports' negative ratings for American Motors' safety did not help.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] During this time, AMC's international sales were expanding.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] From only 18,000 cars five years ago, the 1965 model year AMC sold 74,420 vehicles in Canada, Europe, and Latin America.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] AMC remained the most significant U.S. seller of autos in both France and Germany.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Abernethy also called for the de-emphasis of the Rambler brand because he believed the public associated it too strongly with economy cars and that it was hindering the sale of American Motors' other models at a time when mid and luxury car sales were robust.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] As a result, he ordered that for 1966, the Ambassador and Marlin were to be badged purely as a product of American Motors.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The strategy shift at first seemed to be working because sales of the redesigned 1965 and 1966 Ambassadors improved, even as AMC's overall production decreased from the record level achieved in 1963.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] However, corporate earnings per share were a meager 27 cents per share, the lowest since AMC made its famous compact car comeback in 1958.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Investors received a message of the changing fortune of the automaker when the company's 1966 annual financial report was delivered in a plain brown wrapper, instead of the previous year's glossy cover.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] A completely new design was also slated for the larger 1967 models.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] This strategy added $60 million in retooling costs, a significant stretch for the company.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The latest models shared fewer parts and were more expensive to build.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Abernethy continued his objective to position the new Rebel and Ambassador designs on an equal basis with competitive economy models marketed by the Big Three.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors did not have their own electric car program as did the Big Three, and after some negotiation, a contract was drawn in 1967 with Gulton Industries to develop a new battery based on lithium and a speed controller designed by Victor Wouk.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] A nickel-cadmium battery powered 1969 Rambler station wagon demonstrated the power systems that according to the scientist was a "wonderful car".
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] This was also the start of other "plug-in"-type experimental American Motors vehicles developed with Gulton – the Amitron city concept car and later the similar Electron.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Although the new models were well received by the motor industry media, the last quarter sales for AMC ended September 30, 1966 (AMC was not on a calendar fiscal year) were disappointing.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The company recorded a balance sheet loss of $12,648,000 for the year before Tax Credits and deferred Tax Assets.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] By this time the board had lost confidence in Abernethy due to his vast spending which had unstabilized the company and each year under his leadership the company had suffered substantial financial losses.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] As a result, Abernethy was forced into taking an "early retirement" from American Motors on January 9, 1967.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Chapin quickly instituted changes to American Motors's offerings and tried to regain market share by focusing on younger demographic markets.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Chapin's first decision was to cut the price of the Rambler to within $200 of the basic Volkswagen Beetle.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Innovative marketing ideas included making air conditioning standard on all 1968 Ambassador models (available as a delete option).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] This made American Motors the first U.S. automaker to make air conditioning standard equipment on a line of cars, preceding even luxury makes such as Lincoln, Imperial, and Cadillac.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The company introduced exciting entries for the decade's muscle car boom, most notably the AMX.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] At the same time, the Javelin served as the company's entrant into the sporty pony car market created by the Plymouth Barracuda and the Ford Mustang.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Additional operating cash was derived in 1968 through the sale of Kelvinator Appliance, once one of the firm's core operating units.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Kelvinator divestiture left American Motors a downsized company solely manufacturing automobiles.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Rambler marque was discontinued for the larger 1968 domestic models, leaving only the small Rambler American as the last product to bear the name through 1969.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Rambler brand continued to be used only for export markets, with Mexico being the last market to use it in 1983.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] From 1970, American Motors was the brand used for all American Motors passenger cars, and all vehicles from that date bore the American Motors name and the new corporate logo.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] However, "American Motors" and "AMC" were used interchangeably in corporate literature well into the 1980s.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The branding issue was further complicated when the company's Eagle all-wheel drive passenger cars were marketed as the American Eagle in the 1980s.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] In the late 1960s, Kaiser Industries Corporation decided to leave the automotive industry and sought a buyer for its money-losing Kaiser Jeep division.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors' vice president for manufacturing, Gerald C.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Meyers, headed the team sent to evaluate Kaiser's Jeep factories.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Although opposed by AMC's top management, Chapin made a significant decision in February 1970 to purchase Kaiser Jeep for $70 million.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Although it was a gamble, Chapin believed Jeep vehicles would complement American Motors' passenger car business.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] (The latter being the only Nissan-branded vehicle in the United States until the 1980s when the Datsun name was phased out in favor of Nissan.) Jeep by far had the largest market share of the 4x4 market during this time.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors gained the iconic Jeep brand of light trucks and SUVs, as well as Kaiser-Jeep's government contracts – notably the M151 line of military Jeeps and the DJ-Series postal Jeeps.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors also expanded its international network.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The military and special products business was reconstituted as "American Motors General Products Division", later reorganized as AM General.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1970, American Motors consolidated all passenger cars under one distinct brand identity and debuted the Hornet range of compact cars.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Hornet and the later Gremlin shared platforms.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Gremlin, the first North American-built subcompact, sold more than 670,000 units from 1970 through 1978.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Hornet became American Motors' best-selling passenger car since the Rambler Classic, with more than 860,000 units sold when production ended in 1977.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Hornet platform continued to be built under various models through 1987.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] For a time, both the Hornet and Gremlin could be ordered with Levi's denim interiors.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors supplied Mark VII Limited owner Jack Webb with two Matadors, a sedan and a wagon, for use in his popular television series *Adam-12*, increasing the cars' public profile.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Matadors saw fleet use as taxis, government, police, and fire vehicles in some states.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1973, American Motors signed a licensing agreement with Curtiss-Wright to build Wankel engines for cars and Jeeps.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Starting in 1974, the Matador sedan and station wagon were mildly refreshed, with new boxier front and rear ends, making it full-sized.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] This second-generation model was produced virtually unchanged until 1978.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Sagging sales and tight finances resulted in the discontinuation of the Matador line after the 1978 model leaving American Motors to focus almost exclusively on its Hornet platform-based cars and the Jeep line.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] From 1970, the Rebel and Ambassador were identical from the A-pillar back.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Ambassador continued as AMC's upmarket model with higher trim, more equipment, and air conditioning as standard.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] From the A-pillar forward, the Ambassador was redesigned and stretched 7 inches (178 mm) to become the biggest ever, just as the 1973 Arab Oil Embargo sparked gasoline rationing across the nation.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The additional length was due to a new front-end design and more substantial energy-absorbing bumpers required of all automobiles sold in the U.S.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Sales of all large cars fell due to economic problems and rising gasoline prices.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Ambassador became a full-sized car in 1974 and was discontinued after the 1974 model year, leaving only the Matador as American Motors' full-size offering.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Nash and American Motors made Ambassadors from 1927 through 1974, the longest use of the same model name for any American Motors product and, at the time, the longest continuously used nameplate in the industry.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1974, the first-generation Matador two-door hardtop, known as the "flying brick" due to its poor aerodynamics in NASCAR competition, was replaced with a sleek, smoothly shaped, and radically styled two-door coupe.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The model received praise for its design, including "Best Styled Car of 1974" by *Car and Driver* magazine, customer satisfaction, and sold almost 100,000 coupes over five years.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Matador Coupe shared few components with the Matador sedan and station wagon other than suspension, drive train, some trim, and interior parts.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1974, American Motors's AM General subsidiary began building urban transit buses in cooperation with Flyer Industries of Winnipeg, Manitoba.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] A total of 5,431 *Metropolitan* buses, including 219 electric trolley buses, were built before production ceased in 1979.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Production of diesel buses had ceased in 1978, with only trolley bus production taking place in 1979.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The AMC Pacer, an innovative all-new model introduced in March 1975 and marketed as "the first wide small car", was a subcompact designed to provide the comfort of a full-sized car.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Its pre-production development coincided with tightened U.S. federal passenger emissions and auto safety regulations.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Pacer sold well its first two years with 262,772 combined units sold in the US.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] With the Arab Oil Embargo of 1973, General Motors aborted the Wankel rotary engine around which the Pacer had been designed, as its fuel consumption exceeded that of conventional engines with similar power.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Therefore, American Motors's existing 258 and 232 cu in (4.2 and 3.8 L) AMC Straight-6 engines were used in the Pacer instead.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The fuel economy was better than the expected rotary engine's, but the I6's gas mileage was relatively low in light of the new focus on energy efficiency.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Also, as the Pacer shared few components other than the drivetrain with other American Motors cars, it was expensive to make, and the cost increased when sales fell steeply after the first two years.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Pacer line was discontinued in mid-1980.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] However, "AMC used cars, as far back as 1967, had the advantage of good warranty coverage ... so most owners were conscious of low-cost car maintenance ...
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] AMC units became some of the very best buys on the used car market" by 1975.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The 1977 Gremlin had redesigned headlights, grille, rear hatch, and fascia.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] For economy in the fuel crisis, American Motors offered the car with a more fuel-efficient Volkswagen-designed Audi 4-cylinder engine 2.0 L (122 cu in).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The engine was expensive for American Motors to build, and the Gremlin retained the less costly but less economical 232 cu in (3.8 L) as standard equipment.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] It was a sporty appearance package on the Hornet hatchback featuring upgrades, as well as the 258 cu in (4.2 L) inline six as standard with a choice of three-speed automatic or four-speed manual transmissions.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The 304 cu in (5.0 L) V8 engine was optional with the automatic transmission.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] As all Matadors now received standard equipment that was formerly optional (e.g., power steering, automatic transmission), the "Brougham" package was dropped from 1977.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Optional on the Matador coupe was a landau vinyl roof with opera windows, and top-line Barcelonas offered new two-tone paint.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] For the 1978 model year, the Hornet platform was redesigned with an adaptation of the new Gremlin front-end design and renamed AMC Concord.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors targeted it at the emerging "premium compact" market segment, paying particular attention to ride and handling, standard equipment, trim, and interior luxury.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Gremlins borrowed the Concord instrument panel, a Hornet AMX-inspired GT sports appearance package, and a new striping treatment for X models.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The AMC Pacer hood was modified to clear a V8 engine, and a Sports package replaced the former X package.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] With falling sales of Matador Coupes, sedans, and wagons, their 304 cu in (5.0 L) V8 engine was dropped, leaving only the 258 cu in (4.2 L) Inline-6 (standard on coupes and sedans) and the 360 cu in (5.9 L) V8 (optional on coupes and sedans, standard on wagons).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The two-tone Barcelona luxury package was offered on Matador sedans, and two-tone red paint was introduced as an additional Barcelona option.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Matador production ceased at the end of the model year with total sales of 10,576 units.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Matador was no longer attractive as automakers struggled to overcome economic woes, including continuing fuel price increases and double-digit U.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] For the 1979 model year, the Spirit sedan replaced the Gremlin.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] A new fastback version of the car, the Spirit Liftback, proved successful.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] In December, Pacer production ceased after a small run of 1980 models was built to use up parts stock.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Concords received a new front-end treatment, and in their final season, hatchbacks became available in DL trim.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Concord and Spirit models were dropped after 1983.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] However, Time noted record Jeep sales and a backlog of orders for AM General's buses.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] In July 1977, it was announced that the General Services Administration of the Federal U.S. government had awarded AMC a three-year contract worth $15 million to lease 5,838 cars.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Since the beginning of the fiscal year on October 1, 1976, the GSA had purchased 8,700 cars from AMC for $30 million.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] On October 21, 1977, Roy Chapin Jr. retired, and Gerald C.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] On March 31, 1978, American Motors and Renault announced a sweeping agreement for jointly manufacturing and distributing cars and trucks that would benefit both.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] A month later, American Motors announced that it would halt the production of standard urban transit buses after about 4,300 were sold by its AM General subsidiary over a period of three years.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Environmental Protection Agency ordered the recall of all American Motors's 1976 cars (except those conforming to California emissions regulations) – some 270,000 vehicles— plus 40,000 1975 and 1976 Jeeps and mini trucks, for correction of a fault in the pollution control system.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Total cost was estimated at up to $3 million, or more than AMC had earned the previous quarter.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors lost an estimated $65 million on its conventional (non-Jeep) cars for the fiscal year that ended September 30, 1978, but strong Jeep sales helped the company to an overall $36.7 million profit on sales of $2.6 billion.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] However, American Motors faced costly engineering work to bring their Jeeps into compliance with a federal directive for all 4-wheel-drive vehicles to average 15 mpg‑US (16 L/100 km; 18 mpg‑imp) by 1981.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] In December 1978 the government of Iran, embroiled in the Iranian revolution, cut off oil exports to the world.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] This caused a devastating effect on all American automobile makers and American consumers.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Gasoline prices jumped 52 percent between September and December 1979.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Each of the Big Three (Ford, General Motors, Chrysler) lost money throughout 1979 leading to Chrysler becoming insolvent and considering bankruptcy by September.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Ford survived only because of its European operations, eventually losing $7 billion in domestic sales from 1979 to 1982.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] During the crisis, and with its domestic market share at 1.83%, American Motors struck a deal with Renault, the nationally owned French automaker in October 1979.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] AMC would receive a $150 million cash injection, $50 million in credits, and also the rights to start building the Renault 5 in 1982 (a deal for Renault products to be sold through the American Motors-Jeep dealer network had already been made in 1979).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] In return, Renault acquired a 22.5% interest in American Motors.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] This was not the first time the two companies had worked together.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Lacking a prestige model line in the early 1960s, Renault assembled CKD kits and marketed Rambler cars in France.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] A drop in Jeep sales caused by the declining economy and soaring energy prices began to constrict American Motors' cash flow.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] At the same time, pressure increased on the company's non-Jeep product lines.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The face-lifts and rebranding of American Motors' once-innovative and successful cars were not enough in a competitive landscape that had changed dramatically.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] No longer was the threat limited to the Big Three automakers (General Motors, Ford, and Chrysler).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] In response to the 1979 oil crisis, the Big Three had resorted to importing foreign motor vehicles, mainly Japanese models.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Japanese models were mass-marketed and had lower manufacturing costs.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] By the end of 1980 Japanese manufacturers surpassed Detroit's production totals, becoming first in the world.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Indeed, the share of Japanese cars in U.S. auto purchases rose from 9 percent in 1976 to 21 percent in 1980.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Japanese manufacturers (Honda, Toyota, and Nissan) used streamlined production methods such as outsourcing and Just In Time (JIT) supply-chain management.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] They had new, highly efficient assembly plants in the United States.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] And now they targeted the heart of American Motors' passenger product line: small cars.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] In early 1980, the banks refused American Motors further credit.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Lacking both capital and resources for the new, truly modern products it needed to offer, the company turned to Renault for a $90 million loan (US$351,676,090 in 2025 dollars).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] By September that year, American Motors's U.S. market share had fallen to 1.7%, and in November sales dropped 19.1%.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors warned stockholders that the company could be bankrupted if they did not approve a plan for Renault to acquire as much as 59% of the company.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] On December 16, 1980, American Motors shareholders "overwhelmingly approved making the French Government-owned Renault" their company's principal owner.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Jean-Marc Lepeu, former corporate treasurer at Renault, became vice president for finance at American Motors.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] In September 1981, Jose Dedeurwaerder, a Renault veteran of 23 years, mainly in manufacturing, became American Motors' executive vice president for manufacturing.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] In January 1982, the company's president W.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Meyers as chairman and CEO, and Dedeurwaerder moved up to be president.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] By this time Renault owned 46% of American Motors.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Dedeurwaerder brought a broad perspective at this critical time: he is credited with streamlining many of American Motors' arcane management techniques.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] He also instituted important improvements in plant layouts, as well as in cost and quality control.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Having increased its stake in the company several times to keep it solvent, Renault eventually owned 49% in 1983.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Some view this development as ending American Motors' run as a truly American car company.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] New ownership and management heralded a new product venture for American Motors: a line of modern front-wheel drive cars, designed by Renault, to be produced at Kenosha.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1980, all American Motors cars received a new rust-proofing process using Ziebart as Factory Rust Protection.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The extra protection also included aluminized trim screws, plastic inner fender liners, and galvanized steel in every exterior body panel, along with the unibody getting a deep-dip (up to the window line) bath in epoxy-based primer.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] In August 1979, for the 1980 model year, American Motors introduced four-wheel-drive versions of the Spirit and Concord, calling the collective line the AMC Eagle.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Eagles rapidly became one of the company's best-known products and are considered one of the first "crossover SUVs".
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Eagles used the 2-wheel drive body shells mounted on an all-new platform developed by American Motors in the late 1970s.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Featuring an innovative full-time four-wheel-drive system, it sold best in snow-prone areas.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Sales started strongly but declined over time.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] While the two-wheel drive Spirit and Concord were discontinued after 1983 as the company concentrated on its new Renault Alliance, the Eagle survived for five years longer, albeit only in station wagon form, into the 1988 model year.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] This meant the four-wheel-drive Eagle was the lone representative of the American Motors brand from 1984 until the 1988 model year.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] All the company's remaining output was branded Renault or Jeep.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The last AMC Eagle was built on December 14, 1987.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Renault Alliance was the first joint product of the American Motors-Renault partnership.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Introduced in 1983, the Alliance was a front-wheel-drive Renault 9 compact car slightly restyled for the American market by Dick Teague, mainly to comply with American safety standards, and produced by American Motors at Kenosha.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The car was badged as a Renault, and some cars also carried American Motors badges.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] It was available as a sedan with two or four doors and later as a convertible.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The hatchback, introduced in 1984 and badged as the Renault Encore, was the same as the European Renault 11 model.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The new model, introduced during increased interest in small cars, won several awards, including Motor Trend Car of the Year.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] *Motor Trend* declared: "The Alliance may well be the best-assembled first-year car we've ever seen.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Way to go Renault!" The Alliance was listed as number one on *Car and Driver's* list of ten best cars for 1983.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The positive reception and sales of 200,000 Alliances by 1984 was hindered by the availability of only two body styles.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Alliance was a European-designed car that was not fully suited to U.S. market demands.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The distribution network was also not well supported, which led to the lower quality delivered by dealerships with "disastrous consequences" for the image of the automobiles and high warranty costs because of quality failings, which greatly impacted sales from 1985 to the end of production in 1987.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] After the 1983 model year, American Motors focused entirely on four-wheel drive autos; the company stopped producing rear-wheel-drive cars.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors facilities were then used to assemble the Renault-branded Alliance and Encore compact and subcompact cars.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] For the final 1987 model year, a higher-performance version of the Alliance 2-door sedan and the convertible was sold as the Renault GTA.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] This version had a Renault two-liter engine that was exclusive to it and not shared with the European Renault 9 and 11 models.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Encore models were renamed Alliance Hatchback in 1987.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Alliance and GTA production ended in June of that year, while the Renault 9 and 11 models continued through the 1988 model year in Europe, being replaced by the all-new Renault 19.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] More beneficial to American Motors' future was the introduction of an all-new line of compact Jeep Cherokee and Wagoneer models in the autumn of 1983 for the 1984 model year.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Renault's François Castaing, head of AMC's product development team, designed the new Jeep platform with styling by Dick Teague.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Renault was interested in selling the Cherokee in Europe, but the vehicle needed to be lighter and more fuel-efficient to meet European expectations.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The new XJ weighed 3,100 pounds (1,406 kilograms), due to its unibody construction and lighter components such as the front seats taken from the Renault 9 and 11 and new Renault Alliance.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] AMC's initial forecasts of 40,000 Cherokee and Wagoneer sales were shattered, with sales amounting to 75,000 in their first year.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The three leading off-roading magazines, *Petersen's 4-Wheel & Off-Road*, *Four Wheeler*, and *Off-Road* each named the new Jeep Cherokee as the "4x4 of the year." The popularity of these downsized Jeeps pioneered a new market segment for what later became defined as the sport utility vehicle (SUV).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] They initially used the AMC 150.4 cu in (2.5 L) OHV four-cylinder engine with a carburetor, and a General Motors-built 2.8 L (171 cu in) carbureted V6 was optional.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1986, throttle-body injection replaced the carburetor on the 2.5 L I4 engines.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] A Renault 2.1 L (128 cu in) Turbo-Diesel I4 diesel was also offered.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Starting with the 1987 models, a new 4.0 L (244 cu in) I6 engine, derived from the older 258 cu in (4.23 L) I6 with a new head design and an electronic fuel injection system, replaced the outsourced V6.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors' "new" engine was designed with help from Renault and incorporated Renault-Bendix (Renix) parts for fuel and ignition management.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The 4.0 developed an outstanding reputation for reliability and toughness.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Retained by Chrysler after the buyout, the design received continuous improvements and refinements until its discontinuation at the end of the 2006 model year.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The AMC 4.0 engine saw extensive application in XJ Cherokees and Wagoneers, Grand Cherokees, and Wranglers, and many of those engines saw (or are seeing) extremely long lives, quite a few exceeding 300,000 mi (480,000 km).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Chrysler built the XJ Cherokee until the end of the 2001 model year in the U.S. and until 2005 in China.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Unlike most sport-utility vehicles based on adapted pickup truck designs, the Cherokee XJ SUV came first, and the Comanche was designed as a later pickup truck version.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] Production of the full-sized pickups ceased after 1987.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Grand Wagoneer and 360 V8 engine were dropped after 1991 (the last American-made vehicle whose engine used a carburetor for fuel delivery), and the Comanche was discontinued after 1992.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Significant changes occurred in 1985 as the market moved away from American Motors' small models.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] With fuel relatively cheap again, buyers turned to larger, more powerful automobiles, and American Motors was unprepared for this development.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Even the venerable Jeep CJ-5 was dropped after a *60 Minutes* TV news magazine staged exposé of rollover tendencies under extreme conditions.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors also confronted an angry workforce.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Labor was taking revenge, and reports circulated about the sabotage of vehicles on the assembly lines because of the failure to receive promised wage increases.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] There were rumors that the aging Kenosha plant was to be shut down.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] At the same time, Chrysler was having trouble meeting the demand for its M-body rear-drive models (Dodge Diplomat, Plymouth Gran Fury, and Chrysler Fifth Avenue).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Because they were assembled using the old "gate and buck system" and the tooling could be easily moved, Chrysler could supply the components and control the quality while AMC assembled the car.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Cappy agreed to use some of AMC's idle plant capacity in Kenosha.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] In January 1985, Renault's chairman in France, Bernard Hanon, was dismissed by the government in a shake-up triggered by huge losses as a result of his goal to revolutionize Renault's product strategy in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] He was instrumental in 1981 for the company to invest in AMC and also made Renault a full-line automaker, but this ballooned the firm's debt.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Renault relinquished its number one sales position in Europe, which it held from 1980 until 1983.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] The company had been losing money since 1981 and had fallen to sixth place behind Ford, Fiat, Volkswagen, Peugeot, and General Motors.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Strikes plagued Renault at the end of 1984, and the French government introduced price controls that severely cut the profit margins on cars sold in France, Renault's most important market.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Hanon was replaced by Georges Besse, ex-president of Produits Chimiques Ugine Kuhlmann in France.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Paul Tippett resigned to become president of a textile company.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Dedeurwaerder, president since 1982 and chief executive officer since September 1984, announced at the Paris Auto Show in October 1985, that AMC would begin imports of the innovative seven-seat, front-wheel-drive Espace minivan in the spring of 1986.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] This was part of expanding the range of Renault models that include plans for marketing the Renault Alpine GTA/A510 sports car through select AMC dealers.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] In December 1985, Dedeurwaerder became chairman of AMC's executive committee while continuing as the company's president and CEO.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Joe Cappy was moved up from executive vice president to chief operating officer, and Tippet's position was filled by an ex-Renault vice president, Pierre Semerena.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Semerena made his managerial reputation as a no-nonsense cost cutter.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] The new management responded with tactical moves by selling the lawn care Wheel Horse Products Division and signing an agreement to build Jeeps in the People's Republic of China.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] The Pentagon had problems with AM General, a significant defense contractor, being managed by a partially French-government-owned firm.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] The U.S. government would not allow a foreign government to own a substantial portion of an important defense supplier.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] As a result, the profitable AM General Division was sold to LTV Corporation.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Another milestone within AMC's management was the departure of Dick Teague.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] He was American Motors' design vice president for 23 years - an industry record. he was responsible for many Jeep and AMC designs, including the Javelin, AMX, Hornet, Gremlin, Pacer, Matador coupe, and the Cherokee XJ.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] In France, Renault continued to experience financial trouble.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] The investment in American Motors (including the construction of a new Canadian assembly plant in Brampton, Ontario) forced cuts at home, resulting in the closure of several French plants and mass layoffs.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] In addition, Jeep vehicles were riding an unprecedented surge in demand.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] It seemed to Besse and others that American Motors was on course for profitability.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] However, on November 17, 1986, Besse, who had a high-profile among French capitalists, was assassinated by a member of a French clandestine far-left extremist group, Action Directe.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] AMC's plans to reinvigorate sales with higher-priced Renaults continued for a little longer, with the plan being a three-pronged lineup beginning with the mid-sized Medallion, the larger Premier above it, and the sporty Renault Alpine providing a halo car.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] The Medallion and the Premier both went on sale, but Alpine never made its planned mid-1987 rollout.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Under pressure from Renault executives following Besse's death, Renault's new president, Raymond Levy, set out to repair employee relations and divest the company of its investment in American Motors.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Renault owned 46.1% of American Motors' outstanding shares of stock.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] In 1986, American Motors posted a $91.3 million loss.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] The earlier agreement between Chrysler and American Motors in 1985, under which American Motors would produce M-body chassis rear-drive large cars for five years from mid-1986 through 1990, fed the rumor that Chrysler was about to buy AMC.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] According to the head of manufacturing for Chrysler, Stephan Sharf, the existing relationship with AMC producing a car for a competitor facilitated the negotiations.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] On March 9, 1987, Chrysler agreed to buy Renault's share in American Motors, plus all the remaining shares, for about $1.5 billion ($4,250,878,735 in 2025 dollars).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chrysler made no secret that they were only interested in AMC for Jeep, AMC's new assembly plant in Canada, and AMC's network of 1,300 dealerships nationwide.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] With the sale complete, American Motors became the Jeep-Eagle division of Chrysler on August 25, 1988, and was fully merged as of March 29, 1990.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] The sale came at a time when the automotive press was enthusiastic about the proposed 1988 lineup of Renault, Eagle, and Jeep vehicles and reported that the small automaker's financial outlook was improving.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors' quarterly results for all of 1987 were positive.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chrysler purchased American Motors when the company appeared to be in an excellent financial position with its new product line.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] It was the Jeep brand that Chrysler CEO Lee Iacocca wanted – in particular, the ZJ Gen. of the Grand Cherokee, then under development by Jeep engineers, which ultimately proved highly profitable for Chrysler (the nameplate remains in production today).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] However, the buyout included other attractive deal sweeteners for Chrysler.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Among them was the world-class, brand-new manufacturing plant in Bramalea, Ontario, which offered Iacocca an unprecedented opportunity to increase his company's production capacity at a fire-sale price.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors had designed and built the plant in anticipation of building the Renault 25-based Eagle Premier.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Renault left the U.S. market entirely as a brand in 1987.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Thus, the Renault Medallion was sold through the new Jeep-Eagle division as an Eagle, not a Renault.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] The Jeep-Eagle division was formed from the American Motors Jeep Renault dealer network.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] The Jeep and Eagle vehicles were marketed primarily by former American Motors dealers.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] The American Motors badge was last used on the Eagle Sports Wagon through the 1988 model year, then eliminated, and the Eagle car brand was phased out by 1998.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] The 1954 merger of Nash-Kelvinator Corporation and Hudson Motor Car Company that established American Motors was led by Nash-Kelvinator president George W.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Mason to reap benefits from the strengths of the two firms to battle the much larger "Big Three" automakers (General Motors, Ford, and Chrysler).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] The merger was initially intended to be three-way, with Packard being the number three.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Mason had first discussed the possibility of a merger with Packard president James J.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Nance insisted that if Packard were to join, he would have to be the CEO of the new company.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Mason fully intended to lead the new company, thus the deal did not go through.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Packard acquired Studebaker two months after Nash acquired Hudson.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Mason became CEO and president of the new company, and Hudson's president A.E.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Barit retired to become an American Motors board member.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Mason selected long-time Nash associate and future governor of Michigan, George W.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Roy Abernethy, ex-vice president of sales for Willys, was hired to be vice president of sales.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Following Mason's sudden death on October 8, 1954, Romney took over, reorganizing the company and focusing American Motors' future on a new small car line.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Mason's death also allowed Romney to put an end to any further discussions for a merger between American Motors and Studebaker-Packard.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] By the end of 1957, the legacy Nash and Hudson brands were completely phased out and replaced with the Rambler and Metropolitan brands.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] The company struggled initially, but Rambler's sales took off under Romney.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] A Rambler won the 1959 Mobil Economy Run, and by 1960, was the third-most-popular brand of automobile in the United States, behind Ford and Chevrolet.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] George Romney left American Motors in 1962 to run for governor in Michigan and was replaced as CEO by Roy Abernethy.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Abernethy had been with AMC since the 1954 merger and as vice president of sales was responsible for successfully building AMC's sales and distribution network during the 1950s and early 1960s.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] After two model years (1963 and 1964) of only producing compact cars, Abernethy shifted the focus of American Motors back to bigger and more profitable cars such as the Ambassador line and tried to move away from the perceived negative of the Rambler's economy car image.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] However, the enormous costs of developing the new cars and engines meant American Motors now had problems in securing working capital to keep the company going.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors sales dropped 20% in the first half of 1966, and the firm reported a fiscal six-month loss of $4.2 million on sales of $479 million.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Evans invested more than $2 million because American Motors's stock was selling for only 60% of the company's net worth; thus, he became its largest stockholder and was named its chairman on June 6, 1966, replacing Richard E.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Cross, who continued as a director and chairman of the executive committee.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] In the quarter ending September 30, 1966, American Motors recorded a loss of $12,648,000 before tax credits and deferred tax assets.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] In the face of deteriorating financial and market positions, Abernethy "retired" as CEO in 1967, and Evans "resigned" as chairman.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chapin Jr., the son of Hudson co-founder Roy D.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors' public explanation for the removals was that the two had "stepped aside according to a plan to give a younger team an opportunity to move the company forward".
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chapin took charge of revitalizing the company, and designer Dick Teague economized by developing several vehicles from common stampings.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] The AMC Matador was in reality a facelift of the AMC Rebel, itself derived from the 1967 AMC Ambassador platform.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] While prices and costs were cut, Teague designed new and more sporty automobiles resulting in the Javelin and AMX muscle cars; and the AMC Hornet.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] From 1970 Jeep production complemented AMC's existing passenger-car business.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Under Chapin's leadership, AMC produced all-new compact car designs based on the Hornet platform including the Gremlin and Concord.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Meyers replaced the retiring William Luneburg as president and Chief Operating Officer.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Only 5 months later, upon the retirement of Chapin, Meyers became chairman and CEO on October 21, 1977.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] At the time, Meyers was 49 years old, and became the youngest top executive in the automobile industry.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Meyers abandoned AMC's policy of head-on competition and instead focused on revamping its four-wheel drive vehicles, a market segment left untended by the large automakers, and by acquiring advanced technology.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Meyer's began talks with Renault in 1979 and from 1980, American Motors partnered with the French automaker to help finance their manufacturing operations, obtain much-needed capital, and source subcompact vehicles.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] On December 16, 1980, Renault became the principal owner of American Motors.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] At age 53, Meyers retired from the company in February 1982.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] By that time, Renault controlled 46% of American Motors.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Meyers was succeeded as chairman by former American Motors president W.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] At the time, Tippett was a member of American Motors management for only three years but had overseen almost all vehicle-making operations during his time as president.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Jose Dedeurwaerder, a Renault manager, replaced Tippet as president.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Tippet's tenure as CEO was short-lived and in September 1984, he was replaced by Dedeurwaerder.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] On September 28, 1984, Dedeurwaerder was promoted to CEO, with Tippett remaining on as chairman.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] On February 25, 1985, AMC announced its first full-year profit since 1979.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] The success was short-lived as on July 31, 1985, AMC announced that it had received a $50 million loan from Renault following a second-quarter loss of $70.4 million.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Under Dedeurwaerder, Chrysler entered an agreement with American Motors in 1985 to produce Dodge Diplomats and Plymouth Furys, as well as Dodge Omnis and Plymouth Horizons in American Motors' Kenosha, Wisconsin, plant.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] At the time, American Motors had excess manufacturing capacity.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] In January 1986, Dedeurwaerder was named Renault's executive vice president of worldwide sales and marketing.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] He remained president and CEO, and chairman of the executive committee at AMC until March 23, 1986, when he was succeeded in the former two roles by Joseph E.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] By 1986, Renault had lost $700 million on $22 billion of sales in the U.S. market, and was $9 billion in debt.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] On March 23, 1986, former executive vice president of operations Joseph E.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Cappy was named president and chief executive officer of American Motors.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chrysler acquired American Motors in August 1987.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] The primary task of Chrysler management was to integrate the two companies as quickly as possible.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors' final CEO, was tasked with achieving this by Chrysler president Gerald Greenwald.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] After the buyout Cappy joined Chrysler as group vice president of the new Jeep-Eagle division.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] In 1989, he was named Chrysler's vice president of brand development.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] The following year he became Chrysler's vice president of international operations.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors was forced to constantly innovate for 33 years until Chrysler absorbed it in 1987.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] The lessons learned from this experience were integrated into the company that bought American Motors.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] The organization, strategies, and several key executives allowed Chrysler to gain an edge over the competition.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Even today, the lessons gained from the American Motors experience continue to benefit other firms in the industry.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] There are many legacies of American Motors's business strategies.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors could formulate strategies that industry critics often evaluated as "strokes of brilliance".
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chapin Jr., American Motors realized they were up against the giants of the industry, so to compete successfully they had to be able to move quickly and with ingenuity.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] An essential strategy practiced by American Motors was to rely on outside vendors to supply components in which they had differential advantages.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] This approach was finally accepted within the U.S. auto industry, but only after each of the Big Three experienced the failure of attempting to be self-sufficient.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Another example of American Motors' agility was the ability of management to squeeze money out of reluctant bankers, even in the face of bankruptcy.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] These core abilities helped save the company from collapse and, after each obstacle, gave it the wherewithal to keep it operating.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Ironically, American Motors was never stronger than just before its demise.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors' managers anticipated important trends in the automotive industry.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] It preached fuel efficiency in the 1950s, long before most auto buyers demanded it.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Led by American Motors' Rambler and several European cars, the small car innovation reduced the Big Three's market share from 93% in 1957 to 82% in 1959.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] The company inherited foreign manufacturing and sales partnerships from Nash and continued developing business relations, decades before most of the international consolidations among automobile makers took place.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors was the first U.S. automaker to establish an ownership agreement with a foreign automaker, Renault.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Although small in size, American Motors was able to introduce numerous industry innovations.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Starting in 1957, American Motors was the only U.S. manufacturer to fully immerse all automobile bodies in primer paint for protection against rust, until competitors adopted the practice in 1964.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Even one of American Motors's most expensive new product investments (the Pacer) established many features that were later adopted by the auto industry worldwide.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] These included aerodynamic body design, space-efficient interiors, aircraft-style doors, and a large greenhouse for visibility.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors was also effective in other areas, such as marketing, by introducing low-rate financing.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors' four-wheel-drive vehicles established the foundation for the modern SUV market segments, and "classic" Jeep models remain the benchmark in this field.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chapin drew on his experiences as a hunter and fisherman and marketed the Jeep brand successfully to people with like interests.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] The brand developed a cult appeal that continues.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] The purchase of American Motors was instrumental in reviving Chrysler.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] According to Robert Lutz, former president of Chrysler, the American Motors acquisition was a big and risky undertaking.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] The purchase was part of Chrysler's strategic "retreat-cum-diversification" plan that he states did not have the proper focus.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Initially, the goal was to obtain the world-renowned Jeep brand.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] However, Lutz discovered that the decision to buy American Motors turned out to be a gold mine for Chrysler.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] At that time, Chrysler's management was attempting to find a model to improve structure and operations, *"something that would help get our minds unstuck and thinking beyond the old paradigms that we were so familiar with*".
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] In this transformation, *"Chrysler's acquisition of AMC was one of the all-time great moments in corporate serendipity*" according to Lutz *" that most definitely played a key role in demonstrating how to accomplish change*".
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] According to Lutz (1993), while American Motors had its share of problems, it was far from being a bunch of "brain-dead losers".
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] He describes the "troops" at American Motors as more like the Wake Island Marines in battle, "with almost no resources, and fighting a vastly superior enemy, they were able to roll out an impressive succession of new products".
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] After first reacting with anger to the purchase, Chrysler managers soon anticipated the benefits.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] To further solidify the organizational competencies held by American Motors, Lee Iacocca agreed to retain former American Motors units, such as engineering, completely intact.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] In addition, American Motors' lead engineer, François Castaing, was made head of all engineering at Chrysler.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] In an unthinkable strategic move, Castaing completely dismantled the entrenched Chrysler groups.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] In their place, American Motors's "platform team" was implemented.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] These were close-knit cross-functional groups responsible for the whole vehicle, contrasted with Chrysler's highly functional structure.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] In this capacity, Castaing's strategy was to eliminate the corporate administrative overhead bureaucracy.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] This move shifted corporate culture and agitated veteran executives who believed that Chrysler's reputation as "the engineering company" was being destroyed.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Yet, according to the popular press, by the 1980s, Chrysler's reputation was shot, and in Lutz's view, only dramatic action would change that.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] In summary, Chrysler's purchase of American Motors laid the critical foundation to help re-establish a strategy for its revival in the 1990s.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Top managers at Chrysler after the AMC buyout appeared to have made errors similar to those by American Motors.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] For example, Chrysler invested heavily in new untested models while not keeping up its profitable high-volume lines.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] The American Motors influence also continued at General Motors.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] GM recruited a new executive team to turn itself from near bankruptcy in the early 2000s.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Among the new strategists at GM was Lutz, who understood the importance of passion in product design.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Lutz's new thinking at GM incorporated the systems and structures that originated from American Motors's lean and focused operations.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Renault implemented the lessons it learned from its investment in American Motors.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] The French firm took a parallel approach as it did with its initial ownership of American Motors and applied it to resurrect the money-losing Nissan automaker in Japan.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] In 2009, in a deal brokered by the Obama administration, Italian automaker Fiat initiated a white knight takeover of Chrysler to save the struggling automaker from liquidation.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] The two firms would later fully merge to create Fiat Chrysler Automobiles in 2014, and would further merge with the French firm PSA Group, owners of the Citroën and Peugeot brands, to form Stellantis in 2021.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chrysler revived the "Spirit" name, which was discontinued by AMC after 1983 for use on one of its A platform cars (the Dodge Spirit) from 1989 until 1995.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] The planned Renault Medallion was sold as the Eagle Medallion in 1988 and 1989.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] The full-sized Premier's platform was far more advanced than anything Chrysler was building.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Plymouth almost received their rendition of the LH platform, which was to be called the Accolade.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Still, Chrysler decided to drop this version just before LH production started.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] The Chrysler 300M was likewise a Premier/LH-derived car and was initially to have been the next-generation Eagle Vision until the Eagle brand was dropped after 1998.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] The LH Platform was subsequently re-engineered, using Mercedes-Benz components, into the Chrysler LX Platform, which was the basis for the Chrysler 300, Dodge Charger, and Dodge Challenger.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chrysler's successor Stellantis later revived the Hornet name in 2023 for Dodge as a rebadged variant of the Alfa Romeo Tonale.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chrysler marketed the SJ Jeep Grand Wagoneer until 1991, leaving it almost entirely unaltered from the final American Motors rendition before the buyout.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] The Jeep Comanche pickup truck remained until 1992, while the Cherokee remained until 2001 in the United States.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] The XJ Cherokee was produced in China through 2006 as the Cherokee 2500 (2.5L) and Cherokee 4000 (4.0L).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Although it was not introduced until 1993, the Jeep Grand Cherokee was initially an American Motors-developed vehicle.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Traces of American Motors remained within.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors' Toledo, Ohio, plants continued to manufacture the Jeep Wrangler and Liberty, as well as parts and components for Chrysler, Dodge, and Jeep vehicles (although Toledo Machining and Forge were closed in 2005).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Although heavily downsized, American Motors' main plant in Wisconsin operated as the Kenosha Engine Plant, producing engines for several Chrysler Group products, including the Wrangler.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] The plant was closed as part of the post-bailout restructuring of Chrysler in October 2010.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] The 4.0 L (242 cu in) engine was used until the 2006 model year by DaimlerChrysler in the Jeep Wrangler.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors' technologically advanced Bramalea Assembly and Stamping Plants in Brampton, Ontario, later produced the LX-cars – the Chrysler 300, Dodge Challenger, Dodge Charger, and the now discontinued Dodge Magnum.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Both were retired when the Wrangler was completely redesigned for the 2007 model year.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] AM General, sold by American Motors in 1983, is still in business building the American Motors-designed Humvee for American and allied militaries.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] AM General also built the now-discontinued civilian variant, the H1, and manufactured a Chevrolet Tahoe-derived companion, the H2, under contract to GM, who acquired the rights to the civilian Hummer brand in 1999.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] GM was forced to phase out the Hummer brand in early 2010 due to its bankruptcy restructuring after offering it for sale, but failing to find a suitable buyer.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Although Chrysler introduced new logos for its brands in the 1990s and again in 2010 after the Fiat Group took control of the company, Jeep still uses the American Motors-era logo introduced shortly after American Motors purchased the brand in 1970.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Until the Chrysler purchase, Jeep's logo also featured the American Motors emblem.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Beginning in 1960, American Motors' executive vice president of international operations Roy D.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chapin Jr. embarked on a strong international campaign to set up importation and local assembly operations of American Motors vehicles worldwide.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] In five years, Chapin increased foreign sales to 73,489 cars, which at the same time grew AMC's share of the U.S. export market from 2.5 percent to 14.3 percent.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chapin successfully established or re-established vehicle assembly operations in Argentina, Australia, Belgium (via Renault of France), Chile, Costa Rica, Germany, Iran, Mexico, New Zealand, Peru, Philippines, South Africa, and Venezuela.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] He also strengthened international export operations with exports to the United Kingdom, Denmark, Finland, Iceland, and Norway in Europe, and to countries in the Middle East, the Caribbean, and South America.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] The Rambler Classic would become the basis of Argentina's future national car, the Torino.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] After becoming CEO in 1967, Chapin organized the acquisition of Kaiser Jeep from Kaiser Industries in 1970, with American Motors, thereby inheriting all existing international Jeep operations.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] These helped sustain American Motors during the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p02] While the Rambler marque had been dropped in the United States after the 1969 model year, all export markets retained the Rambler name, with the longest to retain it being Mexico until 1983.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p03] The initial building was built during 1926–27 by the Electric Refrigeration Corporation (subsequently Nash-Kelvinator) with design by Amedeo Leoni, industrial layout by Wallace McKenzie, and tower enclosure and industrial units by William E.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p03] War Department contracted with Nash-Kelvinator to produce 900 Sikorsky R-6 model helicopters.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p03] As part of that contract, a 4.5 acres (1.8 ha) site north of the factory was used as the smallest airport in the world as a flight testing base.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p03] Nash-Kelvinator produced about 50 R-6s a month during the war.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p03] When the contract was terminated at the war's end, 262 helicopters had been constructed.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p03] During Chrysler's occupancy of the complex, it was known as Jeep and (Dodge) Truck Engineering (JTE), including facilities for body-on-frame work as well as testing facilities and labs.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p03] The buildings included 1,500,000 square feet (140,000 m2), approximately one-third devoted to engineering and computer functions.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p03] As of 2007, Chrysler employed over 1,600 people at the complex, moving those operations in mid-2009 to the Chrysler Technology Center.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p03] The property was put up for sale by Chrysler in early 2010.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p03] It was bought by a local man who gutted the building for scrap and left it in a dilapidated state before losing it to foreclosure.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p03] The abandoned building was in possession of the city of Detroit and officials were considering if the industrial site would be more marketable if the building was torn down.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p03] In 2018, the Wayne County Commission approved a land swap that included a new jail complex for the county as well as a potential revival for the old American Motors building.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p03] The era of 1900 until 1925 saw various corporations, in several U.S. states, use similar "American" names, such as American Motor Carriage Company (Ohio, 1902–1903), American Automobile Manufacturing Company (Indiana, 1911–1912), and American Motors Incorporated (New York, 1919–1920).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p03] In 1916, an earlier "American Motors Corporation", apparently unrelated to the more famous later corporation of the same name, was formed in Newark, New Jersey, with Louis Chevrolet as vice president and chief engineer.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p03] By 1918, it was producing cars in a plant at Plainfield, New Jersey.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p03] In 1923, it merged with the Bessemer Motor Truck Company of Pennsylvania into Bessemer–American Motors Corporation, which lasted less than a year before merging with the Winther and Northway companies into Amalgamated Motors.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p03] A new company was formed in Palmdale, California, in 2001.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p03] Registration for the American Motors trademarks was filed in 2001 by this California-based firm.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p03] The company's website specifically claimed no affiliation to the previous American Motors but used American Motors' history and logos on its website.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p03] The website is now dead, and the company's claims to American Motors' trademarks expired in 2005.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p03] The new Chrysler LLC holds a live registration for the name "American Motors", which was applied for in 2005.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p03] The "AMC" wordmark, complete with "A-mark" graphic logo, as was originally used in 1970 and through the late-1980s, was registered and published for comment by Chrysler as of 2010.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p03] Also: Kaiser Jeeps used the AMC 327, Buick 225 ("Dauntless V6"), Buick 350 ("Dauntless V8"), and Willys 134 I4 ("Hurricane").
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p03] The downsized Jeep XJ Cherokee/Wagoneer used the Chevrolet 2.8 L V6 in 1983–1984.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p03] American Motors contracted with Volkswagen to buy tooling for the Audi 2.0 L OHC I4.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p03] Major parts (block, crankshaft, head assembly) were initially purchased from Audi and shipped to the U.S., where American Motors accomplished final assembly at a plant explicitly purchased for the production of this engine.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p03] Sales never reached numbers to justify taking over total production.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p03] American Motors made several changes to the engine.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p03] By contractual agreement, they were prevented from using the Volkswagen or Audi names in association with the American Motors assembled version.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p03] American Motors models historically regarded by hobbyists as particularly "collectible" include the Javelin, AMX, and performance specials such as the 1957 Rambler Rebel, 1965–67 Marlin, 1969 Hurst SC/Rambler, 1970 Rebel Machine, and 1971 Hornet SC/360.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p03] These models enjoyed limited popularity when new, resulting in low production figures.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p03] In January 2007, the AMC AMX was "really taking off in the muscle car market" according to the editors of *Hemmings Classic Car*, and it had "left its mark among AMC collectors' minds as a great alternative" to higher-priced Hemi-powered muscle cars.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p03] The early Javelin (1968–70) stands out from the Ford, General Motors, and Chrysler pony cars.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p03] Mays, automotive historian and author of *The Savvy Guide to Buying Collector Cars at Auction*, the "Wow!
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p03] Factor" is an important and measurable pleasure to an owner whether their car is driven or sits in a climate-controlled garage.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p03] Moreover, the author's collector car, a 1969 Ambassador station wagon, made friends as strangers came to greet and host him as if "long lost kin".
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p03] Mays points out the ready availability of parts for American Motors engines and his experiences in having service done on Ramblers without being charged for the work in exchange for the experience of driving a "sassy Rambler" (a 1966 American convertible) and having pictures taken with it.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p03] Other American Motors models, once somewhat ignored by the hobby, are now considered "future collectibles".
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p03] Examples include the 1959 Ambassador 4-door hardtop station wagon, of which only 578 were produced, and the Jeep Scrambler CJ8, a combined pickup truck-Jeep, of which only a few thousand were made.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p03] The AMC Gremlin is described as having "a cult-like following" in today's collectible car market.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p03] The Gremlin shares components with some other American Motors models, making its repair and restoration relatively inexpensive compared with other "historic cars".
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p03] The AMC Pacer increased in value according to a Pacer owner who is the CEO of a major insurance provider for collector car owners.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p03] There are active Rambler and American Motors car clubs in the U.S. and elsewhere (examples in External Links).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p03] In April 2008, *Hot Rod* magazine released an article claiming that American Motors was in the process of being revived.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p03] The vehicles in the works were to be the AMX, Matador, Ambassador, Pacer, and Gremlin.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p03] It was a popular article, illustrated with drawings of the concept cars entering production and accompanied by plentiful information.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/american-motors-corporation-p03] However, it was later revealed as an April Fools' joke.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/askam-trucks] The company, which was also the first truckmaker in Turkey, ceased production in 2011.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/askam-trucks] Askam was founded in 1962 as a joint venture with 60% ownership by Chrysler, the company originally traded under the "Chrysler Sanayi A.Ş." name.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/askam-trucks] Production of trucks started in 1964 under the Chrysler, Fargo, Desoto, and Dodge brand names.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/askam-trucks] Most of the models built utilized a cab and front end developed by Chrysler specifically for manufacture in developing countries.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/askam-trucks] This cab, in modified form, continued to be used by Askam until its bankruptcy.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/askam-trucks] In 1978, Chrysler sold its share to the local partners and then owners, Tatko, Çiftçiler & Ruşensad.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/askam-trucks] Askam continued production under the Chrysler's license agreement.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/askam-trucks] Most of Askam's products used Perkins diesel engines.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/askam-trucks] After an agreement signed with Japanese Hino Motors in 1991, Askam started production of mini trucks branded "Hino".
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/askam-trucks] When Daimler-Benz and Chrysler merged operations in 1998, Askam changed its name to "Askam Kamyon Imalat ve Ticaret AŞ" in 2002 and continued to produce its products under the Fargo and Desoto brands.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/askam-trucks] Askam produced a variety of Fargo and Desoto heavy and light trucks of its own designs.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/askam-trucks] The numerical portion of the model names (AS250, AS700, AS950) stand for the payload in metric tonnes (e.g.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/askam-trucks] In 2003, Çiftçiler Holding became the only owner of the company after acquiring Tatko and Ruşensad shares.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/askam-trucks] The last trucks were produced in 2011, and attempts were made to sell or revive the company.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/askam-trucks] While trying to buy Askam from Renault Trucks and Temsa, cooperation with the Chinese truck manufacturer Sinotruk came to the forefront; however, none of the opportunities materialized.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] The **automotive industry** comprises a wide range of companies and organisations involved in the design, development, manufacturing, marketing, selling, repairing, and modification of motor vehicles.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] It is one of the world's largest industries by revenue with global automotive market at ~$2.75 trillion in 2025.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] The word *automotive* comes from the Greek *autos* (self), and Latin *motivus* (of motion), referring to any form of self-powered vehicle.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] This term, as proposed by Elmer Sperry (1860–1930), first came into use to describe automobiles in 1898.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] The automotive industry began in the 1860s with hundreds of manufacturers pioneering the horseless carriage.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] Early car manufacturing involved manual assembly by a human worker.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] The process evolved from engineers working on a stationary car to a conveyor belt system where the car passed through multiple stations of more specialised engineers.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] In the 1960s, robotic equipment was introduced, and most cars are now mainly assembled by automated machinery.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] For many decades, the United States led the world in total automobile production, with the U.S.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] Big Three General Motors, Ford Motor Company, and Chrysler being the world's three largest auto manufacturers for a time, and G.M. and Ford remaining the two largest until the mid-2000s.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] In 1929, before the Great Depression, the world had 32,028,500 automobiles in use, of which the U.S. automobile enterprises produced more than 90%.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] At that time, the U.S. had one car per 4.87 persons.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] After 1945, the U.S. produced around three-quarters of the world's auto production.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] In 1980, the U.S. was overtaken by Japan and then became a world leader again in 1994.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] Japan narrowly passed the U.S. in production during 2006 and 2007, and in 2008 also China, which in 2009 took the top spot (from Japan) with 13.8 million units, although the U.S. surpassed Japan in 2011, to become the second-largest automobile industry.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] In 2024, China produced more than 31 million vehicles in a year, after breaking 30 million in 2023, reaching 29 million for the first time in 2017 and 28 million the year before.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] In 2024, China produced the most passenger cars in the world, with Japan, India, Germany, and South Korea trailing.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] This was achieved by Chinese car companies signing joint ventures with foreign manufacturers.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] From 1970 (140 models) to 1998 (260 models) to 2012 (684 models), the number of automobile models in the U.S. has grown nearly twofold.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] Safety is a state that implies being protected from any risk, danger, damage, or cause of injury.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] In the automotive industry, safety means that users, operators, or manufacturers do not face any risk or danger coming from the motor vehicle or its spare parts.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] Safety for the automobiles themselves implies that there is no risk of damage.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] Safety in the automotive industry is particularly important and therefore highly regulated.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] Automobiles and other motor vehicles have to comply with a certain number of regulations, whether local or international, in order to be accepted on the market.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] The standard ISO 26262, is considered one of the best practice frameworks for achieving automotive functional safety.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] In case of safety issues, danger, product defect, or faulty procedure during the manufacturing of the motor vehicle, the maker can request to return either a batch or the entire production run.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] This procedure is called product recall.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] Product recalls happen in every industry and can be production-related or stem from raw materials.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] Product and operation tests and inspections at different stages of the value chain are made to avoid these product recalls by ensuring end-user security and safety and compliance with the automotive industry requirements.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] However, the automotive industry is still particularly concerned about product recalls, which cause considerable financial consequences.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] In 2007, there were about 806 million cars and light trucks on the road, consuming over 980 billion litres (980,000,000 m3) of petrol and diesel fuel yearly.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] The automobile is a primary mode of transportation for many developed economies.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] The Detroit branch of Boston Consulting Group predicted that, by 2014, one-third of world demand would be in the four BRIC markets (Brazil, Russia, India, and China).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] Meanwhile, in developed countries, the automotive industry has slowed.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] It is also expected that this trend will continue, especially as the younger generations of people (in highly urbanised countries) no longer want to own a car, and prefer other modes of transport.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] Other potentially powerful automotive markets are Iran and Indonesia.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] Emerging automobile markets already buy more cars than established markets.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] Power study, emerging markets accounted for 51 percent of the global light-vehicle sales in 2010.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] The study, performed in 2010 expected this trend to accelerate.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] However, more recent reports (2012) confirmed the opposite; namely that the automotive industry was slowing down even in BRIC countries.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] In the United States, vehicle sales peaked in 2000, at 17.8 million units.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] In July 2021, the European Commission released its "Fit for 55" legislation package, which contains important guidelines for the future of the automotive industry; all new cars on the European market must be zero-emission vehicles from 2035.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] The governments of 24 developed countries and a group of major car manufacturers including GM, Ford, Volvo, BYD Auto, Jaguar Land Rover and Mercedes-Benz committed to "work towards all sales of new cars and vans being zero emission globally by 2040, and by no later than 2035 in leading markets".
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] Major car manufacturing nations like the United States, Germany, China, Japan and South Korea, as well as Volkswagen, Toyota, Peugeot, Honda, Nissan and Hyundai, did not pledge.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] The global automotive industry is a major consumer of water.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] Some estimates surpass 180,000 L (39,000 imp gal) of water per car manufactured, depending on whether tyre production is included.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] Production processes that use a significant volume of water include surface treatment, painting, coating, washing, cooling, air-conditioning, and boilers, not counting component manufacturing.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] Paintshop operations consume especially large amounts of water because equipment running on water-based products must also be cleaned with water.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] In 2022, Tesla's Gigafactory Berlin-Brandenburg ran into legal challenges due to droughts and falling groundwater levels in the region.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] Brandenburg's Economy Minister Joerg Steinbach said that while water supply was sufficient during the first stage, more would be needed once Tesla expands the site.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] The factory would nearly double the water consumption in the Gruenheide area, with 1.4 million cubic meters being contracted from local authorities per year — enough for a city of around 40,000 people.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] Steinbach said that the authorities would like to drill for more water there and outsource any additional supply if necessary.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] : US had produced more than 80% of motor vehicles.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] : India overtakes Germany to become 4th largest automobile producer.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] The OICA counts over 50 countries that assemble, manufacture, or disseminate automobiles.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] Of those, only 15 countries (**boldfaced** in the list below) currently possess the capability to design original production automobiles from the ground up, and 17 countries (listed below) have at least one million produced vehicles a year (as of 2023).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] All ten remained as the ten largest car makers by sales until the merger between Fiat-Chrysler and the PSA Group in early 2021; only Renault was degraded to 11th place, in 2022, when being surpassed by both BMW (which became the 10th largest in 2021) and Chang'an.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] The eighteen largest as of 2013 have remained in the top 20 as of 2017, except Mitsubishi which fell out of top 20 in 2016, while Geely fell out of the top 20 in 2014 and 2015 but re-entered it in 2016.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] Mercedes-Benz Group held a combined 6.2% stake in the Renault–Nissan–Mitsubishi Alliance, and the Renault-Nissan-Mitsubishi Alliance also held a combined 6.2% stake in Mercedes-Benz Group until 2021.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] Until 2022, China required foreign automotive firms to form joint ventures in order to access their market.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/automotive-industry] The policy led to quality improvement across the industry.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/barreiros-manufacturer] The company was founded in 1954 as "Barreiros Diesel S.A." by Eduardo Barreiros and based in Madrid.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/barreiros-manufacturer] Additionally a pay-in-kind contract with Polish Star was active in the late 1950s, by which engineless Star chassis-cab trucks were exported to Spain, while Barreiros engines were sent to Poland; the whole resulted in Barreiros-engined Star tractors being sold in China (and Polish trucks in Spain).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/barreiros-manufacturer] Later on Barreiros branched out into the production of passenger cars by means of cooperation (and capital links) with the Chrysler Corporation.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/barreiros-manufacturer] An agreement was reached with Chrysler in 1963 to build the Dodge Dart, allowing the company to enter the car market.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/barreiros-manufacturer] Sold as the Barreiros Dart, it had modified front styling, a four-speed gearbox, and all-around disc brakes.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/barreiros-manufacturer] During that time, the Spanish automobile market was strongly protected, making entering it effectively only possible by domestic manufacturing.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/barreiros-manufacturer] As the 1960s progressed, the range was extended with some smaller models from Chrysler's French subsidiary, Simca.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/barreiros-manufacturer] The Barreiros-made Simca 1000 was launched in 1966, and later the Simca 1200 joined the range (in fact the French Simca 1100, but with a bigger standard engine for the Spanish market).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/barreiros-manufacturer] A total of 17,589 units were manufactured of both models in Spain, they were produced as a knock-down kit imported from Argentina due to the protectionist Spanish regulations of those years.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/barreiros-manufacturer] The Dart and the 3700 were the largest national production cars available in Spain during all production years.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/barreiros-manufacturer] It was an expensive luxury car with very low fuel economy by Spanish standards.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/barreiros-manufacturer] The GL designation was a luxury model, while the GT was the sportier version.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/barreiros-manufacturer] All gasoline Dodges had the biggest engine ever mounted into a mass-production car in Spain, the 225 cu in (3.7 L) Chrysler Slant 6 engine.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/barreiros-manufacturer] The "3700" number is a reference to the 3.7 litres of displacement.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/barreiros-manufacturer] No other six-cylinder engine car has been produced in numbers as numerous in Spain.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/barreiros-manufacturer] A diesel Dart (named "Barreiros Diesel") was also produced.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/barreiros-manufacturer] These models were very basic and very slow, and used the round tail lights from the first-generation Simca 1000.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/barreiros-manufacturer] A station wagon version, as well as other variants (diplomatic motorcade cars, ambulances, hearses, etc.) were produced.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/barreiros-manufacturer] Production of the Spanish Dodge Dart/Dodge 3700 stopped in 1977.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/barreiros-manufacturer] Peugeot bought the Villaverde factory, as Chrysler was divesting European operations in Spain, France, and the United Kingdom.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/barreiros-manufacturer] Spanish Dodges were popular with members of the Franco government during the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/barreiros-manufacturer] Admiral Luis Carrero Blanco was killed on 20 December 1973 while travelling in his Dodge 3700 GT.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/barreiros-manufacturer] On 12 June 1975, Fernando Herrero Tejedor, a Minister Secretary General of the Movimiento Nacional and the politician mentoring Adolfo Suárez, died in a car accident while travelling in his official Dodge 3700 in the municipality of Adanero.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/barreiros-manufacturer] After the last ten Ghia-built Crown Imperial limousines were completed for Chrysler, Ghia sold its tooling to Barreiros.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/barreiros-manufacturer] Barreiros built ten limousines, much like those built by Ghia, and similar to the last ten built by Ghia, built as 1965 models with 1966 exterior styling.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/barreiros-manufacturer] In 1969, Chrysler Europe took complete control of the company.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/barreiros-manufacturer] In 1975, Barreiros became for the first time the sole source for a Chrysler Europe model when the production lines of the slow-selling Chrysler 180 series were moved to Madrid from Simca's factory in Poissy.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/barreiros-manufacturer] Unlike in most other European countries, the Chrysler 180 became relatively popular in Spain.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/barreiros-manufacturer] Barreiros also continued to assemble other Chrysler Europe models for the domestic market, including Simca 1307 (renamed Chrysler 150 in Spain to be more in line with the popular 180) and Simca Horizon.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/barreiros-manufacturer] On the truck and bus side, a full range of light, medium and heavy models was offered, still marketed as Barreiros in Spain and as Dodge or Fargo elsewhere, but eventually the Dodge badge prevailed in all markets.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/barreiros-manufacturer] In 1978, Chrysler Europe was sold to PSA, which subsequently renamed all former Chrysler/Simca models Talbot (so, for example, the Chrysler 150 became Talbot 150).
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/barreiros-manufacturer] Barreiros continued to assemble Talbot car models launched under the PSA reign, such as Talbot Solara or Talbot Samba.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/barreiros-manufacturer] The truck and bus division was sold to Renault, also called RVI, and for a short time, the former original Barreiros models, mostly of them trucks, were sold badged as Renaults / Spanish Renault.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/barreiros-manufacturer] The Barreiros Diesel SA motorvehicle factory at Villaverde in Madrid is now owned by the huge "Renault Trucks (Espana) SA" company where modern Renault trucks and heavy vehicles are produced.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/barreiros-manufacturer] Spanish Prime Minister Admiral Luis Carrero Blanco, who served under Generalísimo Francisco Franco, was assassinated in 1973 while riding in an armoured Dodge 3700 GT by an 80 kg bomb planted by the Basque separatist group ETA.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/barreiros-manufacturer] The car, whose armoured structure resisted the 80 kg dynamite bomb, was blown over the roof of a building, landing in the building's inner courtyard.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/barreiros-manufacturer] The car is now on display at the Army Museum of Toledo.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/chrysler-powertech-engine] The initial design development for the **PowerTech** V6 and V8 engine family was done by American Motors Corporation (AMC) and debuted in 1998 with credit to Chrysler.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/chrysler-powertech-engine] This was the first new V8 engine for Chrysler since the 1960s.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/chrysler-powertech-engine] The companion V6 was basically the V8 with two fewer cylinders, another concept that originated at AMC before the company joined Chrysler.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/chrysler-powertech-engine] These new engines had nothing in common with the Chrysler LA engine V8s, nor the Jeep 4.0 L "PowerTech" I6 engine.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/chrysler-powertech-engine] A 4.7 L V8 came first, available in the Jeep Grand Cherokee, and a 3.7 L V6 version debuted in 2002 for the Jeep Liberty.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/chrysler-powertech-engine] The PowerTech V6 and V8 were direct replacements for Chrysler's Magnum series in the early 2000s, and were also used in the Dodge Ram and started in the 2000 Dodge Durango.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/chrysler-powertech-engine] They were not used in any cars, but were reserved for truck and SUV use.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/chrysler-powertech-engine] They are also known as **Next Generation Magnum** in Dodge applications.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/chrysler-powertech-engine] The PowerTech V6 and V8 engines were produced at the Mack Avenue Engine Complex in Detroit, Michigan.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/chrysler-powertech-engine] E85 compatible versions of some PowerTech engines were developed and used in numerous Chrysler vehicles.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/chrysler-powertech-engine] On April 9, 2013, the last 4.7 L engine was built; ending 15 years of production with over 3 million units built.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/chrysler-powertech-engine] The 4.7-liter version was the first of this family, appearing in the 1999 Jeep Grand Cherokee.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/chrysler-powertech-engine] It has a cast iron block and aluminum heads with two valves per cylinder.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/chrysler-powertech-engine] It uses chain-driven Single overhead camshafts, one in each head.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/chrysler-powertech-engine] It originally produced 235 hp (175 kW) and 295 lb⋅ft (400 N⋅m) of torque.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/chrysler-powertech-engine] The 4.7 L V8 is available with four speed and five speed automatic transmissions and a 5 speed manual transmission.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/chrysler-powertech-engine] The PowerTech was on the Ward's 10 Best Engines list for 1999.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/chrysler-powertech-engine] A "High-Output" version of the 4.7 L PowerTech engine, producing 265 hp (198 kW) and 330 lb⋅ft (447 N⋅m) of torque, was introduced in 2002, first appearing in the Jeep Grand Cherokee Limited as an option and in the Jeep Grand Cherokee Overland as standard equipment.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/chrysler-powertech-engine] This engine was discontinued after the 2008 model year, though the non high output 4.7L V8 engine continued to be available in all vehicles.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/chrysler-powertech-engine] The 2008 4.7 also features other upgrades including a more aggressive camshaft profile, a 74 mm (2.91 in) throttle body, and an improved intake manifold with shorter runners.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/chrysler-powertech-engine] The **EKG** is a 3.7 L V6 version built in Detroit, Michigan.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/chrysler-powertech-engine] It is a 90° V engine like the V8, with SOHC 2-valve heads.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/chrysler-powertech-engine] It utilizes a counter-rotating balance shaft mounted between the cylinder banks to deal with vibration problems of the 90-degree V6 design, as well as use a 30-degree split pin crankshaft to fire the cylinders every 120 degrees.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/chrysler-powertech-engine] It has a cast iron engine block and aluminum SOHC cylinder heads.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/chrysler-powertech-engine] It uses Sequential fuel injection, has roller followers, and features fracture-split forged powder metal connecting rods and an assembled reinforced plastic intake manifold.
[src:chrysler-powertech-engine/chrysler-powertech-engine] The Chrysler 3.7 PowerTech engine used in the 2007–2012 Jeep Liberty KK used a wasted spark ignition system that uses one ignition coil to fire two cylinders.
